<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A commission set up by Channel 4's Dispatches to investigate the
effectiveness of prison as a deterrent has concluded that far fewer people
should be locked up. The six-strong group, including a judge, a chief
constable and the former chairman of the Bar Council, declares that for most
criminals 'prison is neither a remedy nor a deterrent; it is the most
expensive and least effective solution'. The commission not only studied
alternatives to prison but compared British and German experiences (9.00).
Let's hope Episode 2 of Living Islam is less packed and peripatetic than
Episode 1, otherwise we shall end up more confused than when we started
(8.10 BBC2). Today's programme looks back to the great Islamic empires of
the Ottomans and Moguls in the 16th century. Richard Hamilton made the
seminal collage 'Just What Is It That Makes Today's Homes So Different, So
Appealing?' (the man like Charles Atlas, the woman like Mitzi Gaynor, both
surrounded by consumer durables) in 1956. Today on QED Hamilton uses a
computer to make 5,000 laser prints of a 1993 electronic collage (9.30
BBC1).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7812 Motion Picture and Video Production.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
