<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Patten rallies Tory backbenchers
over policy on school tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY MPs rallied behind Mr John Patten, the education secretary, in the
Commons last night when he insisted that schools should proceed with the
tests they are legally required to stage this summer.
He described the attempt made by the National Union of Teachers to promote a
boycott of the tests as 'absurd' and forecast that the 'committed
professionalism of teachers' would result in the law being obeyed.
The government secured a majority of 54 (317-263) to defeat a Labour motion
calling on the education secretary to withdraw the compulsion on schools to
carry out key stage three tests in English and tech-nology.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, had again emphasised the importance of
ensuring that the tests took place.
He said: 'I believe any attempt to sabotage our reforms could damage our
long-term ability to compete, and damage the education of our children.'
Mr Patten rejected a suggestion by Mrs Ann Taylor, the shadow education
secretary, that parents should be balloted on whether they wanted the tests
to take place in the summer.
Challenged by Tory backbenchers on whether she backed calls for a boycott,
Mrs Taylor said she supported the professional and educational case made by
the teachers.
She said the actions teachers took in support of their cases 'must be for
their decision.'
Mr Patten argued that tests enabled parents to establish the progress their
children were making at school, and also helped ministers when deciding the
resources that needed to be allocated to education.
Mrs Taylor acknowledged the value of 'good and appropriate' tests, but
maintained that those which Mr Patten had devised were 'high on
administration and low on educational value'.
Sir Malcolm Thornton (C Crosby), chairman of the cross-party education
committee, said he could understand teachers' frustration but cautioned that
a boycott would do nothing but harm.
He advocated improved consultation procedures for teachers and suggested
that an agreement to make the tests voluntary rather than statutory for the
present year offered a way forward.
Mr Patten assured him that teachers would be able to make their views known
to Sir Ron Dearing, the chairman of the schools curriculum and assessment
authority.
Earlier in the day the Liberal Democrats broadened their campaign for the
local elections with the launch of a paper promising new approaches in
education instead of the current 'division and chaos'.
Mr Don Foster, the party's education spokesman, predicted that there would
be a widespread boycott of the tests by parents as there had been in
Scotland. Agreeing with the concerns that teachers had voiced about the
tests, he added: 'They are the professionals, they are the ones that must
make the judgment about what is best for their particular children - I will
support the judgment they come to.'
The government was defeated by 34 votes in the House of Lords when peers
approved a Labour amendment requiring that people with experience of special
educational needs should be appointed to the funding agency established
under the education bill.
</TEXT>
