<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith calls for Serb ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday increased pressure on the
government for military action against the Serbs in Bosnia by urging the
threat of air strikes to check further Serb advances.
He called for 'a clear ultimatum' to be issued to the Serbs 'that they will
not be allowed to continue with their aggression unchecked - and that if
they do so their lines of supply within Bosnia will be subject to air
attack'.
Mr Smith's comments followed his call last week for an ultimatum threatening
air attacks on Serb communication and supply lines if they did not comply
with a ceasefire. Labour MPs will today debate policy on Bosnia amid
evidence of growing pressure on the leadership for a still more aggressive
stance on Bosnia. Some Labour MPs are demanding the sending of ground
troops.
Mr John Major responded to Mr Smith's call by saying moves such as air
strikes were being 'seriously considered' in talks with allies. But he
warned that 'the road to further action, particularly if that road leads to
military action . . . is a road that is fraught with perils'.
The prime minister feared British humanitarian aid efforts would have to
stop if military strikes began.
Mr Smith said he appreciated the risks, but they had to be set against 'the
possibly greater risks' of inaction.
Mr Major sought to calm Tory MPs' fears about UK troops being sucked into a
prolonged conflict in Bosnia by setting firm parameters for British troops'
involvement in combat. He said the 'only circumstance' in which he could
foresee Britain becoming part of a military operation was if it were under
Nato command, with US participation and backed by a new United Nations
resolution with Russian support.
An escalation of outside military involvement was not yet the policy of any
leading UN government, he added.
Downing Street said cabinet ministers kept policy on Bosnia under constant
review, but officials rebuffed suggestions that Britain would necessarily
fall into line if President Bill Clinton backed air strikes.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, urged Britain to back the UN High
Commission for Refugees' proposals for 'safe havens'.
Earlier, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, said the government had
'extreme reservations' about the use of military force.
He also said he was satisfied that the 2,300 British military contingent was
the right size for the humanitarian tasks required and that he was
discussing with the UN the future of the British Field Ambulance unit,
deployed in Croatia since last May.
</TEXT>
