<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Election reform debate delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROW expected to erupt within the Labour party over proposals that it
back proportional representation for Westminster elections was last night
postponed for a month, Ralph Atkins writes.
Labour's National Executive Committee had been due to discuss next week the
proposal for electoral reform drawn up by Professor Raymond Plant, professor
of politics at Southampton University, following a debate at the
Parliamentary Labour party today.
But after pressure from Labour MPs, the party's leadership agreed that the
PLP should instead debate Bosnia today and proportional representation on
May 12.
Party leader Mr John Smith will now set out his views on the Plant report at
the National Executive Committee meeting of May 19. Party officials were
last night stressing that the delay will not stop a final decision being
taken by Labour conference in October.
A consultation period with Labour members had been promised over the summer
but this will now be truncated.
Last night the Plant committee of senior Labour figures was still finalising
their report. Hopes that damaging splits can be partly ameliorated were
raised after the committee decided there would be no 'minority report' - in
spite of the opposition to proportional representation of several Plant
committee members.
Last month, Plant members agreed to recommend the supplementary vote system,
similar to that used in France.
</TEXT>
