<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / PowerGen chief adds to fears over pits' future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHIEF executive of electricity generator PowerGen yesterday set the tone
for talks which will be crucial for British Coal's 12 reprieved pits when he
said his company would need a 'very attractive offer' to buy extra coal.
Mr Ed Wallis's comments will add to the gloom surrounding the 10,000-plus
miners employed at the dozen pits.
British Coal executives believe they will have difficulty in keeping the
mines open for more than a year even if they can sell 10m tonnes annually to
PowerGen and National Power, the other big generator, in addition to
contracts already agreed.
Executives at the generators have indicated privately that the figure of 10m
tonnes may be optimistic.
Mr Wallis said at an Institute of Energy conference in London yesterday that
with 16m tonnes already sitting in PowerGen's stockyards, additional
tonnages 'would effectively preclude me from reducing those stockpiles to
economic levels'.
He added: 'In fact they would probably rise, incurring significant further
financial penalties in stocking costs and capital. So if British Coal would
prefer us to burn their coal rather than our stocks we will need to see a
very attractive offer.'
Mr Wallis also indicated a strong reluctance to ease back on the use of
orimulsion, the bitumen-based fuel, which he said was the cheapest suitable
fuel and 'other than its sulphur content, the cleanest'.
He said: 'I can assure you that we will do our utmost within the constraints
determined by the Department of the Environment during licence discussions
to convert orimulsion from being a development fuel to a strategic one.'
Neither PowerGen nor National Power has started serious discussions with
British Coal on additional coal tonnages since the government's white paper
on the coal industry. Negotiations depend on the level of subsidies that the
government is prepared to provide. Regulation of utility companies in the UK
is working as intended to deal with the problems of monopoly, and is not in
a state of crisis, Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity regulator,
said.
Prof Littlechild was responding to an article in the Financial Times by Mr
Dieter Helm, director of Oxford Economic Research Associates, in which he
said the regulatory framework 'is in crisis and in urgent need of reform'.
British Gas has changed its interruptible supply contracts to try to
encourage competition in the market. The company says interruptible
customers - which have access to cheap supplies of gas in return for being
cut off at short notice during periods of peak demand - will be able to
switch suppliers with seven days' notice.
People, Page 22
</TEXT>
