<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Homes policy seen to create high-crime estates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT rules on financing affordable homes for rent may turn housing
association estates into neighbourhoods with a high crime rate, the Joseph
Rowntree Foundation says.
In a report published today, the social research organisation warns that
government policies are forcing housing associations to create a new
generation of large estates with heavy concentrations of formerly homeless
people and disadvantaged families.
The report says cuts in government grant mean that housing associations are
increasingly building large new estates to maximise value for money.
Social problems are concentrated on these estates by government regulations
which require associations to allocate 70 per cent of new homes to homeless
families. Associations sometimes give 100 per cent of allocations on new
estates to local authorities in return for cheap land.
Larger estates therefore end up with a high proportion of unemployed and
single-parent families.
The Rowntree report says three out of four new tenants on recently-built
estates are unemployed, and half depend on social security. The average
income of tenants has declined from 73 per cent of the national average in
1981 to 33 per cent on large new housing association estates.
Half the families on such estates are headed by a lone parent, and the
number of children per adult is up to three times higher than the national
average. That makes adequate supervision and control by parents harder, and
increases vandalism, litter, graffiti and more serious crime, the report
says.
'The combination of unfavourable dwelling mix and very disadvantaged new
tenants has produced a seriously unbalanced population mix on new estates,'
it says.
Most housing associations have little experience in managing such large
estates, according to the report. Families with serious social problems on
such estates need additional resources such as estate offices and community
facilities.
The report concludes that smaller schemes, traditionally used by
associations to house disadvantaged and vulnerable families, would integrate
better with existing communities.
Building for Communities. Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End, York YO3
6LP. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
