<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Nissan UK executive denies Pounds 97m fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE DIRECTORS of Nissan UK, the former British importer for the Japanese
carmaker, cheated the Inland Revenue out of almost Pounds 97m corporation
tax in a fraud of 'truly massive proportions' that lasted 17 years, a court
heard yesterday.
Mr Peter Rook QC, prosecuting, told the Old Bailey in London that the fraud
centred on the use of false invoices to increase freight costs charged in
the company's accounts, so reducing profits on which corporation tax had to
be paid.
He said that to conceal the fraud an international money-laundering network
was set up involving bogus shipping agents in The Netherlands and Norway and
ending at two Swiss banks - Credit Suisse and BFG.
Mr Rook was opening the prosecution of Mr Michael Hunt, the assistant
managing director of Nissan UK, who is charged with four counts of
conspiring to cheat the Revenue and making use of false documents. Mr Hunt
denies all the charges.
Mr Hunt was at the centre of the conspiracy, the court heard, with Mr Octav
Botnar, Nissan UK chairman and chief executive, and Mr Frank Shannon, the
company's former finance director. Mr Botnar was the 'prime mover' but Mr
Hunt, as his 'number two', was party to the fraud from start to finish, Mr
Rook said. A warrant for Mr Botnar's arrest was issued last year but could
not be served because he had moved to Switzerland.
Earlier this year Mr Shannon pleaded guilty to cheating the Revenue of
Pounds 17m corporation tax. His admission was evidence of a fraud against
the Revenue, Mr Rook said.
In 1971 Nissan UK won the British franchise to import cars from the Nissan
Motor Company. Until 1975 it paid for the cars with a single 'cost,
insurance and freight' payment. In 1975 it varied this agreement, allowing
it to arrange its own freight charges. The intention was to enable the fraud
to take place, Mr Rook said.
In the years that followed a total of Pounds 219m was extracted from Nissan
UK by fabricating invoices which increased the genuine freight charges by
between 40 per cent and 60 per cent on each occasion.
The conspirators set up an international laundering operation to cover their
tracks.
Mr Rook said: 'The trail leads to two Swiss banks where the conspirators
would divide the spoils of the fraud.'
Mr Walter Schmicki, a Credit Suisse banker, and Mr Kurt Vogelsang, a manager
of BFG in Basle, were party to the fraud, he continued.
The trial continues today and is expected to last at least three months.
</TEXT>
