<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / N-plant ruling sought from attorney-general
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ATTORNEY-general will be asked to step into the controversy over British
Nuclear Fuels' new Thorp nuclear reprocessing plant at Sellafield, in a move
that could further delay the plant's operation.
The Department of the Environment has been advised by lawyers that it may
need to consider the wider economic and social case for the plant, as well
as environmental implications, if it is to avoid the risk of judicial review
which could be prompted by legal action from pressure groups.
It has emerged in the past few weeks that the government's legal advice
about which factors it should take into account conflicts with that received
by BNF and may conflict on other points with that received by pressure
groups. The environment department is preparing to ask the attorney-general
for an opinion on which is strongest.
Greenpeace, the pressure group, said last night: 'We have got a legal
opinion that there must be a wide-ranging government inquiry looking at all
the issues.'
Whitehall observers believe the government is determined to avoid the risk
of judicial review, even though formally weighing up the overall case for
Thorp could delay a decision about whether to give it the go-ahead until
autumn.
BNF said yesterday: 'We are waiting for the pollution inspectorate to
deliver its report (on the recent public consultation) to the Environment
Department. We believe that all necessary issues will then have been
covered.' It added: 'If there is another delay it will be expensive.'
The inspectorate's report, which is expected to go to Mr Michael Howard,
environment secretary, in the next two months, addresses only the
environmental and health questions about the plant's operation.
Separately, the cabinet office has been co-ordinating meetings between
senior civil servants from the environment, trade and industry and
agriculture departments and the Foreign Office to look at the wider economic
and diplomatic issues.
Pressure groups have criticised the lack of open ministerial participation
in the debate so far. An environment department decision that these wider
discussions need to be brought formally into the Thorp decision would pave
the way for ministerial-level meetings on the issues.
However, environment ministers would have to erect a 'Chinese wall' during
those meetings between their judicial role in evaluating the inspectorate's
report and their views on the wider questions.
</TEXT>
