<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Law firm set up with links to accountant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW law firm with close connections to Arthur Andersen, the international
accountancy network, is to start operations this summer.
The link between Garrett &amp; Co and Andersen could pave the way towards the
creation of the first multi-disciplinary partnership between lawyers and
accountants if professional rules - which are under review  - are relaxed.
Mr Colin Garrett, managing partner, said he was sending job offers this week
to four or five senior lawyers and expected to start taking on clients in
two or three months' time.
Two of the professionals would be partners and the remainder senior
associates. Three would specialise in commercial law, one in property and
possibly another in employment. Advertisements placed in February said each
post would pay up to Pounds 120,000.
Garrett &amp; Co is independent of Andersen but based in its offices in London,
and expects much of its work to come through Andersen referrals.
Andersen has already established a number of associations with law firms in
other EC countries, including SG Archibald in France and Friehalter, Kruger
&amp; Co in Germany.
The 1990 Courts and Legal Services Act removed a statutory ban on mixed
practices but left professional bodies free to make their own rules, subject
to scrutiny by the Office of Fair Trading.
A proposed European Commission regulation that would establish a new form of
association for the professions has brought the issue back to the top of the
agenda.
Law Society rules prevent solicitors from entering into multi-disciplinary
partnerships with other professionals, but it is consulting on relaxing the
rules.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales allows mixed
partnerships if 75 per cent of the partners are accountants. The Law Society
is thought to favour a similar condition for solicitors.
</TEXT>
