FT  21 APR 93 / Single union deal at Scotch plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST single-union agreement in the Scotch whisky industry has been
signed between William Grant and Sons and MSF, the general and technical
union.
Workers at the Glenfiddich plant in Paisley, Strathclyde, voted
overwhelmingly that the MSF should have sole negotiating rights at the
company.
Seventy four per cent backed the MSF although the union has only 19 per cent
membership among the workforce. Fewer than 7 per cent of the workers chose
the TGWU general union and 11 per cent the AEEU engineering union.
The MSF said: 'The result suggests an overwhelming endorsement of MSF's
negotiating skills and support services.' But it brought strong criticism
from local officials of the TGWU and AEEU.
The ballot was held by the company with the support of all the unions at the
plant, which agreed to abide by the verdict of the workforce.
Mr Roger Lyons, MSF general secretary, said: 'This deal is important because
the terms are not being dictated by management.'
William Grant insisted it wanted a single-union agreement at the new whisky
plant being opened at Strathclyde Business Park 30 miles from the Paisley
site.
</TEXT>
