FT  21 APR 93 / Fraud squad warns of loan scam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND YARD'S fraud squad is warning businesses about the activities of
confidence tricksters who promise to arrange large loans but disappear with
the advance fees.
The latest twist in a long line of cheap-loan frauds involves bogus forms
purporting to show that US Treasury bearer bonds are available as security
for loans which will never be advanced.
It is estimated that 50 or 60 advance fee fraudsters are operating in London
and that perhaps a dozen have switched to the US bearer bond mode of
operation.
The fraud squad says advance fees for arranging the financial packages may
amount to 1 per cent to 2 per cent of the loan involved, or a flat rate of
Pounds 250,000 or Pounds 500,000. After the fee has been handed over the
loan - which may run into tens of million of pounds - never materialises.
The fraudsters have targeted business people who are desperate to raise
finance but have failed to do so through more conventional channels such as
banks or venture capital institutions.
The fraud squad's warning is also directed at professional advisers. The
fraudsters have taken in the lawyers and accountants advising their victims
with the help of bogus evidence that US bearer bonds are available as
security.
Bearer bonds are a popular vehicle for this type of fraud because they do
not show the owner's name.
As evidence that they own or control such bonds the fraudsters have been
producing copies of US Treasury PD 1832 forms. Among indications that the
forms are bogus are that they would have been used for registered
securities, not bearer bonds, and that they have expired.
One characteristic of these frauds is that the victim may be led to believe
that overseas lenders have been found who charge abnormally low interest
rates. Another is that the package involves the fraudster promising to
invest the loan overseas, apparently in order to provide a strong income
stream.
Another inducement offered is that having this secured loan will help the
victim obtain other finance.
The fraud squad is investigating two cases of fraud using PD 1832 forms. It
says these latest variants of advance fee fraud are reminiscent of the ICC
290 and 292 frauds perpetrated in the mid 1980s.
</TEXT>
<XX>
