<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Manufacturers lift investment in innovation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH manufacturers started to increase investment in innovation last
year, before the latest signs of economic recovery started to emerge, a
survey by the Confederation of British Industry and National Westminster
Bank has found.
The more encouraging picture for UK corporate spending on innovation and
research and development, which companies expect will continue this year,
was welcomed as further evidence of an increase in manufacturing confidence
and activity.
Between 1989 and 1991 companies had cut spending on innovation and R&amp;D but
there was a marked upturn last year. Dr Bryan Smith, chairman of the CBI's
research and innovation committee, said the survey - conducted among 425
companies in October and November last year - said the findings were
consistent with evidence of improved business conditions found in other
surveys.
He said: 'We hope the results also reflect a fundamental recognition of the
importance of innovation to companies if they are going to compete
successfully in increasingly tough world markets.
'The prospects for sustaining economic recovery in the medium term hinge on
the competitiveness of manufacturing industry and its ability to develop new
products and processes. That is what makes these results so encouraging.'
Although the survey showed a significant balance among companies reporting
increases in capital investment to support innovation last year, most did
not expect spending to rise substantially this year. Most non-manufacturing
companies expected to reduce innovation investment.
Innovation Trends. CBI, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford St, London WC1A 1DU.
Pounds 20 CBI members, Pounds 40 non-members.
