<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Businesses lack computer failsafe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR IN five British businesses and public-sector organisations do not have
viable contingency plans for computer failures, a survey published yesterday
revealed.
In spite of the critical role computer systems play in most of the
organisations surveyed, barely half had so much as a written contingency
plan to cope with serious computer malfunctions.
The findings come from a survey of 421 UK organisations conducted this year
by Loughborough University for International Business Machines.
Excluding users - notably in the financial and public-services sectors  -
obliged by law to have plans, only 42 per cent were found to have adopted
formal plans. One in five had an untested plan, while a further 15 per cent
of plans were held to be 'doubtful' as they had not been recently updated.
The researchers say: 'With the pace of technological change, it is doubtful
if any plan will remain completely viable for more than six months. Yet only
27 per cent of the organisations had completed plans that recently - nearly
a third of plans were more than two years old.'
Ironically, computer services companies were among the worst performers  -
only 39 per cent had a plan, and 14 per cent a viable one. Local authorities
and research companies also performed badly - only 18 per cent of councils
had a tested plan.
Only in the financial services and utilities (gas, water, electricity and
power generation) sectors were more than a third of plans deemed to be
viable.
A recent survey sponsored by the Department of Trade and Industry said
British business losses through breaches in computer security and physical
damage to systems were running at more than Pounds 1.6bn.
More than eight in 10 of the organisations claimed to have computer
insurance, but the report says cover tends to apply to hardware even though
'greater damage usually results from corruption of data or consequential
losses'.
Up The Creek. Charles Barker, 56 Dean Street, London W1V 5HJ. Free.
</TEXT>
