<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / World Trade News: EC and US will make last try to block ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Leon Brittan today will make one final attempt to head off a US ban,
scheduled to go into effect tomorrow, on EC companies bidding for US
government procurement contracts.
After two days of meetings in Washington, the EC Commissioner yesterday said
he and Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, had failed to reach
agreement. The latter insists the sanctions will be imposed tomorrow, unless
the EC agrees to waive discriminatory provisions in its new utilities
directive.
The two trade officials, who were clearly weary, briefed journalists after
meetings had run for four hours longer than expected. They said that,
although Sir Leon was returning to Brussels late yesterday, they would speak
by telephone once more - at noon today Washington time (4 pm GMT) - in a
last effort to settle.
Sir Leon is due today to report on the talks to a full meeting of the
European Commission in Strasbourg. EC member states are divided over whether
to retaliate against the US if Washington implements sanctions tomorrow.
The UK, Germany and the Netherlands are concerned about a possible trade war
with the US, while France is more inclined to take an aggressive stance if
confronted by sanctions. A senior EC official said it was likely that
France's hand would be strengthened if the US were to go ahead with
sanctions.
Despite their failure so far to reach agreement, Sir Leon and Mr Kantor seem
to have achieved a comfortable informal relationship. They bantered with
each other and the press, while laying out a schedule for a series of
bilateral and quadrilateral meetings designed to achieve agreement on a
comprehensive pact over tariff cuts, in time for the July summit of the
Group of Seven industrial countries.
The two said they had 'exchanged views' on various issues, including steel
and Airbus, but they were vague about the details. Mr Kantor expressed
satisfaction that the EC was 'nearing completion on all the steps it needs
to take' towards an earlier agreement on oilseeds.
Sir Leon insisted that substantial progress had been made on the Uruguay
Round of trade liberalisation talks.
The two will meet again on May 7, when Mr Jacques Delors, EC Commission
president, will be in Washington to meet President Bill Clinton. The
Brittan-Kantor meetings will broaden, possibly to include Canadians and
Japanese, at the end of May, and in Paris on June 1-2.
</TEXT>
