<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / BNL sends special team to Argentina
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL), the state-owned bank whose branch
in Atlanta made billions of dollars of clandestine loans that helped to fund
Iraq's military build-up, has sent a special team of executives to Argentina
in the wake of suspected irregularities that could involve a loss by BNL of
as much as Dollars 100m (Pounds 66m).
Separately, US investigators from Congress and government agencies have told
the Financial Times that they are also looking at BNL's Argentine operation,
partly to see whether any of the bank's funds in Buenos Aires, the Argentine
capital, were used to help finance the nuclear-capable Condor 2 missile
project undertaken by Iraq.
The BNL affair has focused so far on the bank's Atlanta branch. It is the
first time there has been any suggestion of a possible link with its
operation in Buenos Aries.
Between 1987 and 1989, letters of credit handled by BNL Atlanta provided
funds for the Condor missile and other Iraqi weapons projects.
In Rome yesterday, the bank said it was unaware of any links between BNL's
operations in Atlanta and Buenos Aires.
In Buenos Aires, meanwhile, a magistrate yesterday asked his Rome
counterparts to help him investigate relations between the Italian foreign
ministry and several Italian companies that did business in Argentina. One
of the companies took part in the Condor 2 missile project and benefited
from Iraqi loans made by BNL Atlanta.
Among the BNL executives despatched to Argentina are some of the people who
were sent by BNL in 1989 to the US to investigate the Atlanta case. The
Atlanta trial of Mr Christopher Drogoul, the former BNL manager indicted in
connection with the Iraqi scandal, is expected to begin in September.
Mr Davide Croff, a senior BNL executive in Rome, said the present focus for
the team sent to Buenos Aires is on the restructuring and management of the
branch network and related insurance businesses. The BNL network includes 88
branches in Argentina acquired in 1987 and once owned by Banco Ambrosiano,
the bank that crashed in 1982 in a scandal involving the Vatican bank.
The precise nature of the suspected irregularities in Argentina has not been
disclosed but Mr Croff said the work in Buenos Aires included the parent
company in the US making a BNL capital injection to cover potential losses
which he could not quantify and which he said he preferred to describe as
'restructuring costs'.
He added that the Rome bank had no evidence of possible links between funds
from BNL Argentina and com-panies that worked on Iraq's Condor 2 missile
project.
</TEXT>
