</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
New Zealand's new takeover panel has recommended that it be given sweeping
powers to protect shareholders, especially minority interests, writes Terry
Hall in Wellington.
In a recommendation to parliament it urges that legislation be passed which
includes requiring anyone who acquires 20 per cent of the voting rights of a
company to make an offer for the rest of the shares at the same price. At
present, companies or individuals are able to buy shares in a target company
at different prices until they gain control of a majority of the shares.
