<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Bank Negara chief defends forex loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK NEGARA, Malaysia's central bank, has defended itself against criticism
that it has gambled on foreign exchange markets with resulting massive
losses in its special reserves, writes Kieran Cooke in Kuala Lumpur.
In its annual report for last year, the bank said it had suffered a MDollars
2.7bn (Pounds 686m) contingent liability on forward foreign exchange
transactions. A special reserve and contingency funds had plunged from more
than MDollars 10bn at the end of 1991 to MDollars 753m a year later. Mr
Jaffar Hussein, Bank Negara's governor, said a stronger Malaysian dollar,
containing inflation and sharp value changes in reserve currencies had been
mainly responsible for the fall in the special reserves. He said most of the
losses were book losses only.
</TEXT>
