<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Green themes recognised in Queen's awards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES selling dress-makers' dummies, pizza crusts and genetically
improved breeding pigs are among this year's winners of Queen's awards for
export achievement and technological development.
More than 150 businesses have won awards for their success in these
categories and, for the first time, for advances in environmental
protection. The Financial Times group has also received its sixth export
award.
With the government championing an export-led recovery, the majority of
winners received their awards for selling overseas.
They include small companies, such as AE Arthur, of King's Lynn, Norfolk,
which sells adjustable fashion dummies around the world, and Canadian Pizza
Crust of Salford, which supplies pizza bases and fillings.
The first 12 winners of the new award for environmental achievement reflect
a cross-section of green themes. They include products or processes to clean
up industrial effluents, reduce air pollution, save the ozone layer and cut
the use of chemical pesticides.
Survey, Pages 11-20
</TEXT>
