<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / Waigel calls for EBRD to be more accountable: Attali told of
bad image and need for 'good housekeeping'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, ROBERT PESTON and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, LONDON, STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A CALL for greater account-ability and openness in the way decisions are
made at the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development was made
yesterday by Mr Theo Waigel, Germany's finance minister.
At the same time, Mr Waigel, who is chairman of the EBRD'S board of
governors, told Mr Jacques Attali, the bank's president, he was concerned
about criticism directed specifically at its expenditure on new offices in
London.
'Mr Waigel stressed his concern about the (press) criticism of the bank and
how it was creating a bad image,' a finance ministry official said. 'He also
said there was a need for 'good housekeeping'.'
Mr Attali faced further criticisms from Mr Henning Christophersen, EC
economics commissioner and an EBRD governor, who said yesterday that reports
on EBRD spending decisions were 'embarrassing' and that the Commission was
very worried about apparently 'insensitive expenditure'.
In London, one of the bank's directors, who represent the countries which
own the bank, said Mr Attali had only with great reluctance agreed that the
bank's audit committee should conduct a thorough review of the Pounds 55.5m
(Dollars 84m) spent on fitting out its new London offices.
The review is expected to take less than three months, a director said, and
its findings are likely to be published.
Last week the directors made three other demands:
That the three board committees, covering audit, remuneration and finance,
should have more powers to scrutinise bank executives' actions and
consideration should be given to setting up a special budget committee;
That Mr Pierre Pissaloux, director of the budget, corporate planning and
also Mr Attali's chef de cabinet, should give up some responsibilities;
That the budget-making process should start earlier in the year.
Directors said they were disappointed Mr Attali wanted to negotiate on these
points rather than agreeing to them immediately. At the board meeting on
Monday, the US director, Mr William Curran, criticised Mr Attali for not
apologising for the high spending. He said it was 'the minimum' he would
have expected.
Mr Christophersen said the question of low disbursements to central and
eastern Europe was 'particularly preoccupying'. The EC had 'already taken
steps to strengthen the bank's budgetary control processes, to ensure that
expenditure will be easier to justify'.
The commissioner also told MEPs last night that shareholders should be given
more information about the day-to-day running of the bank, and that 'if
necessary' they would order an inquiry. However, shareholders would await
the management's explanation of the budgetary situation at next week's
annual meeting.
Mr Waigel's meeting with Mr Attali, which had been planned before last
week's revelations about the bank's spending on decorating its London
headquarters, was more concerned with the EBRD's record in the former Soviet
Union and in eastern European countries.
The meeting appeared to have allayed German finance ministry suspicions that
the EBRD replicates the World Bank and other international financial
institutions, and so is superfluous.
'If you ask me if the bank is necessary now, well, this used to be a hard
question to answer,' an official said. 'We have this institution. We should
work with the bank. It is useless to say we should abolish it. The key thing
is to maximise its efficiency, and make it more flexible.'
Although finance ministry officials admitted EBRD disbursements in eastern
Europe had been slow, 'the bank should not be criticised for taking too
little risk', an official said. 'Being careful about investments is a good
thing.'
But the official believed the focus could be more on money for small and
medium-size enterprises in Russia and east Europe.
</TEXT>
