<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / UK conduct within ERM criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BASLE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN must give independence to the Bank of England and agree to abide by
ERM rules if it wants any future membership of the European exchange rate
mechanism to succeed, the chairman of the committee of European Community
central bank governors has warned.
Mr Wim Duisenberg, in an interview with the Financial Times, said Britain,
during its short-lived ERM tenure, had reduced interest rates on nine
occasions, 'a couple of times too many'. Other EC nations complied with EC
operating rules by increasing borrowing costs on occasion to keep their
currencies in line with the D-Mark.
While the pound was welcome to rejoin the ERM, Mr Duisenberg thought it
would be in the UK's interest to make the Bank of England rather than the
Treasury responsible for interest rate decisions so that these matters were
taken out of the hands of politicians.
He rejected claims made last year by Mr John Major, the prime minister, and
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, that Britain's ERM exit reflected 'fault
lines' in the system.
The EC governors had concluded that the ERM was technically sound and that
it was in Europe's interests to stick with it despite the recent pressures,
Mr Duisenberg said. 'We have looked at the system with a magnifying glass
but we have not found any fault lines.'
He was also critical of statements during the turbulence from various
governments, including the UK, stating their firm opposition to
realignments. 'If you make statements, you need to stick to them,' he said.
Mr Duisenberg, governor of the Dutch central bank, was speaking in Basle as
the governors' committee concluded in its annual report that EC states made
mistakes in their efforts to calm financial markets during the exchange rate
crises last autumn and early this year.
During the unprecedented strains which forced Britain and Italy out of the
ERM and led to the devaluation of the Irish, Spanish and Portuguese
currencies, the report says governments gave the impression that 'policy
measures to counter tensions were being taken on a piecemeal basis, with
insufficient attention devoted to the credibility of the parity grid as a
whole'.
The document paints a bleak picture of economic activity across the EC this
year.
Economic verdict, Page 3
Observer, Page 25
</TEXT>
