<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Eurotunnel hits at TML over threats of delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH and French con-struction companies were yesterday accused of
blackmail in threatening to delay the opening of the Channel tunnel in
support of longstanding claims for extra payments.
Eurotunnel, which will operate the tunnel, said delays in opening meant that
it could have to raise up to a further Pounds 850m by the end of 1995.
The company said the delays meant that the forecast cost until opening had
risen by Pounds 300m since last autumn to Pounds 8.4bn. This compared with
an original 1987 forecast of Pounds 4.8bn for the project.
Sir Alastair Morton, Eurotunnel's chief executive, said he could not predict
when the tunnel would open. This depended on the contractors' willingness to
co-operate in testing and commissioning the tunnel railway, which was
already largely built.
The opening date has been postponed several times from the original target
date of May 15 this year. Sir Alastair said: 'Only a few a weeks ago
contractors accepted in negotiations that it would be possible to start
running services for heavy goods vehicles from mid-January.'
According to Mr Frank Cain, Eurotunnel executive responsible for
construction of the project: 'Contractors now say that all services will
start at the same time next June.'
Mr Joe Dwyer, chief executive of British construction group Wimpey and joint
chairman of Transmanche Link, the consortium building the project, dismissed
allegations of blackmail as 'astounding nonsense'.
'Sir Alastair is well aware of the principal causes of delay, notably the
many and major changes to safety and performance specifications throughout
the tunnel's construction.'
Delivery of railway carriages to carry cars under the Channel is halted over
a claim for extra time and payments which TML says has been caused by design
changes.
Eurotunnel says that bridging finance will be needed to compensate for the
loss of revenue caused by a delayed opening. This might be raised partly
from shareholders and partly from banks. The amount of money to be provided
by banks, however, is likely to be very limited.
Eurotunnel planned to issue free warrants later this year which would allow
its 630,000 shareholders to buy more shares in the company at an agreed
price. The aim would be to generate about Pounds 200m when the warrants were
exercised next year.
A further Pounds 350m-Pounds 400m would need to be raised by the end of
1995. This would leave an estimated Pounds 200m-Pounds 250m to be found
before the company expected to generate enough from services to cover
operating costs and interest charges. This point was not expected to be
reached until 1997.
The final Pounds 200m-Pounds 250m could form part of a larger rights issue
as Eurotunnel sought to refinance its large bank borrowings once the tunnel
has opened.
It is the first time Eurotunnel has indicated how much extra cash it may
need to raise once the tunnel opens. The money would be in addition to the
Pounds 7.3bn already raised from banks and Pounds 1.6bn from shareholders.
Sir Alastair said the Channel tunnel group would not succumb to pressure
from contractors, which had even more to lose from delaying the opening than
Eurotunnel itself. Failing an agreement, the contractors would have to start
funding construction work themselves until their claims could be settled,
which could take years. Contractors will have to start paying damages after
August 15 for late delivery. This could total about Pounds 200m by next
June.
TML is seeking an extension to the contract to prevent Eurotunnel applying
for damages. Sir Alastair confirmed yesterday he was prepared to sue the UK
and French governments and BR and SNCF for failing to satisfy terms of
railway contracts or the concession under which Eurotunnel will operate the
tunnel.
London stocks, Page 44 See Lex
</TEXT>
