<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (27): Route to zippier graphics -
. . . For Zoom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Z is for the last word in graphics: zoom in and see the detail. Better
still, rotate it, explode it into components, animate it, change its colour,
freeze it, and drop it into a document, surrounded by text.
Producing graphics used to be a painfully slow and limited business,
restricted by the power of the processor, the resolution of the screen, and
the fairly limited capabilities of the software. A decade ago it was a
triumph to present two pie charts on the screen with associated text. Now it
is possible to see a video running on a workstation, complete with sound.
This is partly due to the explosion in desktop computer power, enormous
advances in screen resolution, and the development of associated peripherals
such as colour printers.
Computer graphics are the icing on the cake for some users, who simply want
to make their presentations zippier. For others in the printing and
pre-press industries, the leaps made in the processing of graphics and
images have revolutionised their business.
NEW APPLICATIONS
Skills that took years to acquire have been outdated by rapid changes in
technology, and seem to belong to another century rather than a few years
ago. With the spread of low-cost CD-ROM and video disk hardware, and
software packages to create interactive applications, multimedia techniques
are becoming affordable in everyday applications.
Image processing was happening 15 years ago, but using 32-bit processors was
beyond the reach of all but specialised businesses. Computer-aided design,
CAD, is one of the few areas where the hardware costs more than the
software, due to the processing power needed to plot a three-dimensional
image, and constantly re-calculate it on the screen for rotation or to show
different views.
More casual users, for whom graphics are an occasional tool for business
presentations, still struggle to get the text in the right place on the
slide. Products such as IBM's Storyboard opened up a Pandora's box of filmic
and animation effects in the mid-1980s, making them comparatively easy to
use.
Graphics vendors have removed one of the most tedious tasks, that of
entering data, by integrating graphics with other applications. The ability
to use data which originates elsewhere has become essential. WordPerfect's
Presentations, for example, can take data from other packages, such as Lotus
123.
Animation has become commonplace, but ease of use is still an issue. Lotus
Development's own Freelance package now incorporates a range of 32 animated
effects, such as wipes, fades, flying texts, and 'canned' animations such as
a spinning globe, which can be customised with text. The magnifying glass
icon provides 'zoom' with close-up detail.
'We've designed Freelance so that people can get good results in half a
hour,' says Steve Jack, European brand manager for graphics at Lotus
Development. He adds that people have better things to do than fiddle around
working on presentation slides late into the night, so Lotus has used
multimedia techniques to create an animated, interactive tutorial.
COMPUTER POWER
Steve Morton, technical director of SAS Institute in the UK, sees computer
power as the main factor holding back the rising tide of interest in
animation, currently being fuelled by IBM and Microsoft. SAS Institute's
SAS/Nvision software produces 3D computer graphics and animation, creating
models, rendering images, and animating scenes. It evolved from a US film
animation product, Neo-Visuals, acquired by SAS Institute in the late 1980s
to incorporate the animation technology into its own SAS information
delivery software.
'At the moment there is little interaction with our standard applications
for information delivery: you can capture and freeze a business graphic, and
then animate it,' explains Morton. 'To be sensible, it requires specialised
3D graphics processors, still a relatively expensive option on workstations.
What we envisage is that the ties with live data will become closer, with
luck co-inciding with the availability of cheap 24-bit graphics cards for
PCs, which would make the technology affordable and practical for business
users.'
Some users already incorporate graphics into every aspect of their work.
Products such as Parametric's Pro/Engineer is typical fo the new generation
of Unix products that integrates the entire design-through-manufacturing
process. But the Macintosh still leads in visualisation with products such
as Abvent's multimedia Zoom, Autodesys' Form-Z, and Electric Image's
animation software.
Innovation Design Engineering Opportunities, Ideo, uses graphics and
animation in every stage of designing products. The technique Ideo calls
'interaction design' applies to pocket mobile phones and microwave ovens as
much as to screen interfaces.
'Whenever we design a product with a chip in it, we simulate it to make it
more satisfying to use,' says John Stoddard, head of design at Ideo.
Ideo uses Macintosh products, Studio 32 to design, and then Macro-mind
Director to 'visualise' the display or control panel, and simulate the very
behaviour of the product in use. A full-time psychologist assists with the
testing process.
'The design is based on solid scientific practice as well as having that
creative leap which gives the users pleasure and satisfaction,' says Mr
Stoddard. The process also cuts down documentation. Mobile phones commonly
come with a hefty 100-page manual whereas Ideo's self-explanatory Dancall
boasts a mere six pages. In the 1990s, users are being offered an exciting
but very confusing convergence of several different technologies, as the
usage of desktop PCs for graphics and presentations expands to include
multimedia, and other technologies seep down from the 'top-end' of CAD and
print-publishing.
The last word belongs to Barnaby Page, editor of a magazine called Pre-Press
which keeps 8,000 professionals in the print, design and reproduction
industries up to date with the latest in graphics and processing
technologies. He has identified a shift in the attitude of users.
'People saw the computer as a means of producing paper, but now they are
beginning to see the computer file itself as the original. The by-product
might be paper, or just as easily, an animation on CD-ROM.'
Once developed, he points out, an animation has several applications, such
as a business or sales presentation, or in a freeze-frame form in a printed
brochure. He points to Kodak's Photo-CD, a scanner for CD-ROM, as a typical
example of how technologies draw together to create new potential - 'in
fact, there's nothing new in the technologies themselves . . . it's the
combination of them that's powerful.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-14121</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDTCVAG3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930420
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (26): Easier ways to build
systems - . . . For Yourdon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ED YOURDON, a pioneering American computer scientist, gave his name to a
method for breaking down the design of a computer system into a set of
components and the relationships between them.
The Yourdon Method is, however, only one among many structured approaches to
building computer systems - all of which fall under the general heading of
computer-aided software/systems engineering, (CASE).
As long ago as the late 1960s, computer scientists recognised that building
information technology systems of any size was a complex task. But they also
saw that it could be simplified if it were viewed as an engineering
discipline rather than an arcane craft.
This important breakthrough in thinking spawned a succession of
'methodologies' - each of which claims to make systems building at least
more manageable, if not easier.
Most software in the past was produced in an informal environment where much
was left to the individual programmer or systems designer. This was
unsatisfactory because it often led to complex systems which could only be
understood by those who built them. If a programmer or designer left,
maintenance became a problem.
Starting in the military and aerospace sectors, the formal approach to
systems and software production has spread throughout the industry since the
early 1970s. The original goal was to improve programmer productivity - the
tools concentrated on code generation and project management. But it became
evident during the 1980s that the 'engineering' approach had broader
potential.
Concepts such as 'information engineering' - where a company's entire
operation is modelled as a set of formal processes - gained credibility.
James Martin, one of its leading advocates, saw that companies could gain
competitive edge in their markets if they could identify applications which
brought high return on investment.
The advanced design and production tools now available to systems builders,
provide the technology to support this vision and produce such applications
quickly.
Nowadays, most serious systems and software development is undertaken within
a formal 'engineering' framework. The final goal of the system is defined,
the systems needed to achieve it are specified and the criteria for its
delivery and support are established.
CASE methods like Yourdon provide the theoretical foundation. They provide
the link between the informality of the real world and the formality of the
computer model.
In its fullest sense, CASE embraces every stage of the development of a
system from the identification of a business need, through development, to
maintenance and 'live' running.
All CASE methods use the concept of the formal software 'life cycle' as
their base and attempt to enforce rigorous design principles throughout.
A system is broken down into a set of components which can be assembled to
create a complete system. The development of the individual components is
managed within the context of the whole system to ensure consistency.
This is a broad area of activity which can be broken down into two distinct
areas: 'upper' CASE - which covers business and system design; and 'lower'
CASE - which covers the development process.
The 'upper' CASE tools and disciplines are used to gather data and evolve a
specification in the form of a data dictionary or system repository. They
may also be capable of simulating a completed system to demonstrate to
users. The 'lower' CASE tools use the design 'dictionary' to generate code
for the final live system.
Any design changes must, of course, be made at the 'upper' level to maintain
the integrity of the design.
At its most ambitious, so-called 'integrated CASE' combines both the design
tools and the production tools in a 'seamless' continuum.
But most early experiences of CASE have, for historical reasons, involved a
mixture of tools and disciplines. A company might like a particular design
tool, but want to use a code generator from a different supplier.
Not surprisingly, this has led to the need for a certain amount of
standardisation of CASE tools, the methods they support and the systems for
which they can generate applications code.
IBM's Application Development (AD)/Cycle is the most ambitious initiative in
this direction.
There are also international standards efforts aimed at defining a
specification for a general-purpose system 'dictionary.' This will make it
possible for a wide range of 'upper' CASE tools to build specifications for
a wide range of code generators.
This is still a long way from the complete automation of the system-building
process. CASE requires a lot of human interference - to get round quirks in
design, which cannot be accommodated by the technology, or to meet the need
for special-purpose code which the code generator cannot produce. It is also
complicated by the change in the underlying infrastructure of information
technology. Applications are no longer built for a single computer - or even
to meet a single need. In the 1990s, they can be spread across a wide range
of technologies from a laptop computer to a giant mainframe.
</TEXT>
<XX>
