<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (25): A battle between rival
contenders - . . . For X-Windows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BANKS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE coming together of six leading computer companies to produce the Common
Open Software Environment (COSE) raises the significance of the X-Windows
display management standard to the position of potential lead technology in
graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
As more computers are linked together in distributed systems, the need for a
common interface to the services available on such systems, the prime
objective of the COSE initiative, grows more pressing.
The COSE members, Hewlett Packard, IBM, Santa Cruz Operation, Sun
Microsystems, Univel and Unix Systems Laboratories, all have a vested
interest in seeing the X-Windows standard prosper, for all either use it
directly as the basis for their graphical user interfaces, or sell the
operating environment on which it runs.
The X-Windows standard itself started life over ten years ago as two
separate research projects in the US.
Project X at Stanford University in California was aimed at creating a
windowing system, while Project Athena at MIT in Boston aimed at developing
a network-independent graphics protocol that would provide cross-network
services in a mixed-vendor environment.
The two projects were closely complementary and the windowing system was
soon absorbed into the cross-network graphics protocols to form what first
appeared as X-Windows in 1986.
It is now the broadly accepted standard for windowing and graphics
management on Unix-based systems, with a pan-industry consortium of Unix
suppliers and users supporting it.
The key to its acceptance has been the underlying objective of making it
vendor-independent. This has had some drawbacks in driving it through to
universal adoption, however, particularly in the PC arena. Unlike
Microsoft's Windows system, which has the specific PC platform as its sole
target, X-Windows has had to be written as the underpinning specification:
the method by which graphics such as an individual window are to be
displayed and how user actions such as clicking on an icon are to be
handled.
Unlike Microsoft Windows, however, it does not specify the 'look and feel'
of the system. This has led to the inevitable rise of different user
interfaces. Following on from the Unix industry splitting in to two main
camps: Unix International and the Open Software Foundation, the X-based GUI
has been promoted in two different forms, respectively Open Look and
OSF/Motif.
These have been the subject of considerable marketing hype between the rival
contenders. Sun Microsystems has been the leading proponent of Open Look,
and because of the company's dominance in the workstation market (and the
bundling of Open Look with its products) it justly claims that the system is
the most widely sold X-based GUI.
LEADING SUPPLIERS
OSF/Motif, on the other hand, is specified by the largest number of Unix
system suppliers, including IBM, Hewlett-Packard and Digital Equipment, and
there is growing evidence that is the most likely version to be specified by
users.
The leading supplier of Motif-based windowing systems is IXI of Cambridge,
whose X Desktop windowing system is specified by most of the leading
suppliers. IXI was recently bought by the Santa Cruz Operation (which
already integrates X Desktop into its own Unix) thus giving the company a
significant seat on the councils of the COSE grouping.
Perhaps the most important aspect of X-Windows as a standard is the fact
that it has been specifically designed to work in a client-server
environment. Windowing systems running on a stand-alone machine such as a PC
are self-contained; the user takes an action within a window, and the
application in question is there on the same machine.
In a client/server environment, it is highly likely that the users actions
on a workstation will affect or use an application running on a different
system. The results of the action may, in turn, have to be passed to a
different application on yet another system on the network.
In this situation, there is a need for a management system which not only
ensures that the users actions, and the results, are presented correctly on
the workstation, but also ensures that the users' instructions to and
demands upon the various applications running elsewhere on the network are
correctly routed and acted on.
The flexibility and vendor-independence of X-Windows can also be exploited
to create wider distributed systems than those based solely on Unix
platforms and applications.
For example, a number of companies have developed software tools which allow
X-Windows-compliant windows to be opened within a Microsoft Windows
environment on a PC.
The leading suppliers of this technology are UK companies such as VisionWare
of Leeds and JSB Software of Macclesfield. Their tools allow users to work
at a networked PC, using all the familiar applications and productivity
tools of the Windows environment and, when required, open a X-compliant
window on to a Unix server.
This provides great flexibility, in that the users keep a familiar working
environment on the PC and gain access to the wider, more comprehensive power
of the distributed network through X-Windows.
There is also the full cut-and-paste capabilities of Windows available
between the PC applications and those X-compliant applications on the
network.
</TEXT>
<XX>
