<DATE>930420
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (22): Key role in commercial
computing - . . . For Unix
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIX is an operating system: the software that controls the computer
hardware so that business systems can be loaded and run and given access to
data files on disc, to printers and to other resources.
However, Unix is special: it is being worked into a standard so that it can
run on different computers of all sizes.
Computer manufacturers have traditionally sold their own operating systems
with their own computers. This has tied customers in, because moving to
another supplier has meant large redevelopment of application programs.
This tradition has also limited users' choice of program packages. Huge
development costs have restricted package suppliers to offering their
products on a very limited number of operating systems.
All this is gradually changing, thanks to Unix, an unlikely candidate for
such a key role in commercial computing. For one thing, Unix was originally
developed more than 30 years ago by a researcher at AT&amp;T privately working
on a computer game. Ken Thompson found a mainframe computer unsuitable for a
game for a single user, so he wrote an operating system for a spare DEC
minicomputer.
As an operating system supporting on-line working on relatively cheap
minicomputers, Unix gained a considerable following in universities,
especially as AT&amp;T provided it at little cost.
Meanwhile, the heart of the system was rewritten in the 'C' programming
language, which runs on a variety of computers. Unix could now be moved from
one computer to another without massive redevelopment. However, this meant
universities and companies adapted it in different ways for their own needs.
In 1980, Microsoft turned Unix into a serious product by launching a version
called Xenix and other suppliers started showing interest.
AT&amp;T now sought to regain control and in 1983 launched a version called
System V to try to set a standard.
The standards movement started rolling slowly in 1984, when X/Open was
formed as a world-wide body of users and suppliers to gather contributions
on standards, especially relating to Unix, and publish specifications based
on the best proposals.
However, the Unix world was split in 1988 when two rival industry groups
were formed: Unix International, led by Unix originator AT&amp;T and Sun
Microsystems, and the Open Software Foundation, with top computer
manufacturers IBM, Hewlett Packard and DEC among the founders.
Unix International based its future on the Unix System V developed by AT&amp;T
through its Unix System Laboratories subsidiary.
The Open Software Foundation meanwhile built its Unix by combining the best
pieces of software from its member companies. The organisation argued that
there were risks in allowing a single company, AT&amp;T, to control Unix.
Computer manufacturers joined one group or the other and there was open war.
However, user pressure brought a truce, if not peace. This was marked in
1991 when Unix International adopted the Open Software Foundation's
Distributed Computing Environment, a piece of software which enables
different computers running different operating systems to work together.
This and other agreements mean there is now considerable compatibility
between versions of Unix in the way different versions run application
programs.
In March this year there was significant progress when all sides announced
they would work towards common standards at the user level: in particular,
to ensure common user screens and facilities - known as graphical user
interfaces - the adoption of the same networking products, plus agreement on
standards in the handling of graphics, multimedia (the linking, for example,
of tradit ional magnetic disc files with pictures from CDs) and the
management of company-wide distributed systems.
Six companies from the rival factions, including world computer industry
leader IBM, Hewlett Packard - which claims over 40 per cent of the world
Unix market - AT&amp;T's Unix System Laboratories and Sun Microsystems,
announced they would combine the best of their products in these areas,
present a single specification to X/Open and then make that specification
available to anyone - free of charge. In addition they committed themselves
to dropping further development of their own products and standardising on
the agreed specifications.
RED-LETTER DAY
The six companies' announcement drew instant support from another two-dozen
organisations, many of which made equal commitments to adopt the standards -
'this is a red-letter day for open systems and a sign that the open systems
industry is showing a bit of maturity at last,' said Mr Bernard Hulme, head
of marketing and support for Europe at Unix specialist software house Santa
Cruz Operation.
Mr Geoff Morris, chief executive of X/Open, said that by basing the proposed
standard on established products the six suppliers ensured that the
specification should be available by June.
The six are organising a seminar for applications software producers in
October and expect to launch products based on the standards in the first
half of next year.
The spectre at the Unix feast is Microsoft, ruler of the personal computer
operating system market as developer of MS-DOS and Windows and due to
announce its more sophisticated NT in a month's time.
Unix suppliers are pooh-poohing NT. Yet at the announcement by the six
partners in March they took every opportunity to attack Microsoft, even when
answering questions on other topics. And only the week before the chief
executive of Unix International, Mr Peter Cunningham, was in London with a
presentation which specifically brought the NT challenge to the audience's
attention and then proceeded to knock it down. Unix is available on
computers ranging from powerful desk-top machines to mainframes. The focus
of NT is expected to be desk-top machines and office processors managing
local files and programs and running networks.
If there is to be a battle at office and even desk-top level between Unix
and NT, as many observers believe, last month's announcement means that the
Unix army at last seems to be approaching unity.
This in turn means that whatever the outcome of the battle, the customer
looking for open systems already seems set to be the winner.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
