<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (19): Big impact on the market -
. . . For Risc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SINCE the mid-1980s, reduced instruction set computer (Risc) design has
become the basis for most - if not all - workstations above personal
computer level, for departmental systems and for even more powerful
machines.
The trend was set by one of the oldest and one of the newest computer
manufacturers: in 1986, Hewlett-Packard based its entire future computer
range on Risc; and a year later, Sun Microsystems shook the workstation
market with a product based on its own Risc processor called Sparc, or
Scalable Processor Architecture.
Sun went some way to establishing Sparc as an industry standard through
licensing and marketing deals with the likes of ICL, Xerox, Fujitsu and
Amdahl; in addition, the company's growing significance attracted AT&amp;T as a
leading shareholder.
The move towards Risc is in many ways a move right back to very earliest
days of computers. In the 1940s and early 1950s, processors and memory
worked at the same speed. A programmer's instructions were read from memory
one at a time and processed by hardware which was wired to handle particular
functions, such as add, load and store.
However, advances in processor technology dramatically outpaced the speed at
which program instructions could be retrieved from memory. Processors would
be idle, waiting for the next instructions.
So in the late 1950s and 1960s, processors were given expanded instruction
sets, stored as so-called microcode in very fast local memory. This
development came as high-level programming languages such as Cobol were
making their mark: such languages enabled the programmer to write
complicated statements - for example, to instruct a computer to compare two
items of data and take different action depend ing on the result.
So now, instead of retrieving and processing a simple instruction and then
having to wait for the next one, the processor was fed with a complex
instruction and spent so much time breaking it down into simple microcode
instructions and then processing them that the former idle time was
eliminated.
This new approach was seized on with such enthusiasm that by the mid-1980s a
big mainframe computer might have 300 to 500 instructions built in, compared
with 15 to 30 in the earliest machines. Today these big systems are known as
Cisc - complex instruction set computer - machines.
However, continuing rapid progress in hardware technology meant the memory
speed issue gradually disappeared. In fact the move towards complex
instruction sets was such that in some cases the processor now keeps the
memory waiting: the opposite of the situation that prompted the move to
complex instruction sets.
When Hewlett-Packard came to design its Risc range, it analysed 900bn lines
of programming code from all application areas running on a dozen
manufacturers' computers. And it discovered that just 20 per cent of
instructions accounted for 80 per cent of processing.
Such a finding means manufacturers can in effect return to the 1940s
principle of wiring a small number of often-used simple instructions into
the processor and largely dispense with microcode. This means faster
processing.
The removal of microcode from a microchip also means more of the
instructions can be located together on the same chip, so data being passed
from one instruction to another moves within the same chip and not between
separate components. This, again, increases speed.
Risc has had a big impact on the market, not least because it has taken off,
45 years after its original heyday, at the same time as the Unix operating
system (see also the Unix entry in this A-Z). Suppliers of Risc systems of
all sizes are standardising on Unix.
SUCCESSFUL PRODUCTS
New companies - notably Sun Microsystems - have been born and have
flourished, thanks to Risc products. Established manufacturers have launched
whole ranges of Risc products: Hewlett-Packard staked its entire future as a
computer manufacturer on Risc with its 1986 announcement and a commitment to
Unix; and IBM has had success with its RS/6000 range, launched in 1990.
Unlike the personal computer market, where manufacturers have largely
settled on Intel processors, the Risc business is fragmented on the hardware
front, although several suppliers are trying to establish their products as
standards. Sun Microsystems in particular has a big following and MIPS
Computer Systems has struck some deals.
Microelectronics specialist Motorola is a leading supplier to Risc system
builders. Motorola is also part of an as yet unknown quantity: a consortium
with IBM and Apple which is working to get IBM's RS/6000 Risc processors on
the market as electronic components for other computer and workstation
manufacturers.
The use of Risc designs, continuing advances in technology, competitive
pressures and the rapid emergence of Unix as a standard operating system
have taken the prices of basic powerful workstations down to around Pounds
2,000, just as the personal computer market is set for new turmoil. Intel,
purveyor of processors to the personal computer industry, is about to unveil
its top-end Pentium processor and, in May, Microsoft will launch its NT
operating system.
The two old-timers, Risc and Unix - both dating back more 30 years - will be
key partners in the battle for tomorrow's desk-top computing market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
