<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (20): New ways to protect vital
information -  ..For Security
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPUTER security is entwined with the myth of the teenage hacker. The
callow youth who cuts through acres of code and plants irreverent and
destructive messages in a critical computer system.
There are real threats to the security of information technology. They come
from more mundane sources than the hacker, but can inflict more damage than
conventional thieves.
Robert Schifreen has carved out a respectable career for himself as a
security consultant. Eight years ago he was in court charged with hacking
into the Duke of Edinburgh's electronic mailbox and signing off as '. . .
His Royal Hacker.'
The authorities were not amused and Schifreen and his fellow hacker pursued
the matter to the House of Lords before their exploit was dismissed as a
harmless prank.
Today, Mr Schifreen is in demand for solid commercial advice. But he
stresses the practical side of security risks - 'telephone hacking is not as
important as the fact that someone can walk up to your office, copy your
files onto a floppy disk, wander out and read them at leisure,' he says.
In order to protect information, everything connected to it must be secured.
Encryption, hiding data behind a sequence of code-words, can lock out
unwanted users. Restricting access to the office makes it less rewarding for
a data intruder to chase up those code-words. But with the rise of local
area networks and computer clusters built around one powerful processor
acting as a central server it has become difficult to 'partition' data
access.
Keith Marsden is managing director of Braintree, a Cheshire-based software
house specialising in security issues. He echoes Schifreen's view that
security is about more than technology - 'it's not about hackers. The most
dangerous person in a company is the one who's under stress and bearing a
grudge.'
Marsden believes security begins with an awareness of personnel, their
problems and grievances and a knowledge of just how far they can delve into
the company's data. Braintree produces Auditor Plus, a software security
product for Digital Equipment computer networks. Costing upwards of Pounds
12,000 per installation, Auditor is not cheap. But it takes a novel approach
to the issue of systems security.
Installed on a network Auditor checks each user's level of authorisation to
assess their potential access to data. The effect is to provide the user
with a harsh remind er of just how many people can see confidential files.
Marsden has found that demonstrating Auditor is an effective, if alarming,
sales tactic - 'one potential user gave us the name of a file that only four
senior staff could access officially. Auditor ran through the system and
reported that 100 people could access it]'
Auditor began life five years ago after the Cern nuclear research laboratory
in Geneva was victim to unauthorised access. The perpetrator destroyed files
and caused significant damage. The lesson was not lost on other sites
guarding irreplaceable data. Auditor's second sale was to the European Space
Agency.
Reuters exists to sell huge volume of data. It uses Auditor to prevent
unauthorised browsing into its huge reserves of historical market data. Paul
Andrews, a Reuters systems manager, has instructed the program to trawl
through his system every 30 minutes. It reports on whether individual
authorisation levels have been changed to enlarge access.
Given that information is the raw material his organisation thrives on, Paul
Andrews has no trouble justifying the cost of IT security measures. And he
finds that Reuters clients are well aware of the benefits of careful
security planning - 'when I say we're using a dedicated security product it
gives the clients an added sense of well-being.'
A lack of adequate security procedures can have unexpected consequences. Bob
Hay, a former police chief superintendent, is chairman of the Federation
Against Software Theft. His organisation was established to highlight the
issues involved in unauthorised copying of software. Bob Hay points out that
computer security extends to protecting an organisation's reputation. If
employees engage in widescale copying of software, the company will be held
responsible.
Both GEC Marconi and Mirror Group have found themselves on the receiving end
of Fast investigations. The answer, says Hay, is to set up a software
management charter.
'Register all software bought by the company and carry out regular audits of
what copies are running,' he says. The European Security Forum is evidence
of the weight that blue chip companies attach to data security. Including
Barclays Bank and British Steel among its members, ESF organises workshops
to pool opinions. In the past three years members have allocated Pounds 2.5m
to the organisation.
LESSONS LEARNED
Alan Stanley is managing director of the ESF. He admits that the Virgin
Atlantic-British Airways conflict highlighted a data security breach. BA is
an ESF member, and it managed the computer data bank that contained
passenger booking files for Virgin.
Alan Stanley attempts to draw a positive lesson from the embarassing case of
a prominent ESF contributor breaching recognised standards of
confidentiality in pursuit of commercial gain. He believes Virgin failed to
appreciate the vulnerability and value of its data.
'When you contract-out a service, security is not always the first
consideration. You have to know who's doing what, and what risks the out
side contractor is taking on board.'
Virgin was livid that BA drew sensitive information from the booking system.
The data was used to analyse the profitability of Virgin routes as well to
approach customers. Virgin said it was poised to bring an action against BA
under the Data Protection.
Given the sharp rise in outsourcing of computer maintenance, it's worth
assessing the loyalty of non-employees. They may be perfectly honest, but
less inclined to understand the value of security. Contract staff can
discuss sensitive passwords over mobile phones and leave identity codes
written down for their colleagues. Cited by security consultants as common,
these lapses prove that it pays to keep up a barrage of reminders on the
vital subject of security.
</TEXT>
<XX>
