<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (17): It's not such a simple
issue - . . . For Piracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BANKS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the fundamental problems with software piracy is that most 'pirates'
never realise that this is what they are. It is part of the nature of
software that a program can be copied by one individual, passed on to
another, and the first person still retains their original copy - so how can
it be pirating, for nothing has gone missing?
It is, of course, not theft but breach of copyright and is now treated in
law in broadly the same way as breaches of other copyright in areas such as
writing and music. But while most people are well aware that, if they
photocopy a book or tape a piece of music they are breaching copyright, when
it comes to computer software this does not always register.
Why? Partly it is the industry's own fault. The PC industry in particular
has tended to use a marketing theme along the lines of 'all this technology
for next to no cost.' It is but a short step for many to assume that
software is 'free.'
The industry has also often made its licencing so complicated, particularly
where multiple copies might be required by the user, that copying is simply
the easier option. The other main reason, as implied by recent survey
figures from FAST, the Federation Against Software Theft, is that most
'pirates' simply do not realise that they have actually carried out the act
of piracy.
FAST is made up of around 150 of the leading software suppliers, plus a
growing number of corporate users. The FAST survey has shown that the
majority of offenders are what it defines as ordinary users, often people
using computers for work and passing round within their company applications
that are relevant to their tasks.
Interestingly, the next biggest group of offenders are those that really
should know better, company MIS managers with a tendency to be what FAST
ironically calls 'budget-conscious.' Despite appearances in the press,
unscrupulous resellers, students and dedicated computer hackers in practice
account for less than a quarter of all offenders.
FAST is still more than interested in the activities of such people, and has
recently launched a big crackdown on market and car-boot sale traders who
sell copied applications quite openly. The survey has indicated, however,
that while it should not lose sight of those targets, a shift in focus is
now needed. In short, the corporate users who do not realise they are doing
anything illegal have now become FAST's prime target.
A corporate membership scheme was launched last year and to date FAST has
dealt with some 4,000 enquiries. Two hundred of these have already resulted
in the applicants becoming corporate members of FAST. One of the claimed
advantages of corporate membership is that the software industry members at
last get a method of directly hearing corporate users' problems with such
important factors as licencing agreements and documentation.
Both of these, and in particular the complexity of licencing applications
for use across multiple users on a network, are cited as reasons why
corporate users sometimes end up acting illegally. It also has side benefits
for the corporate users themselves. Not only do they learn how not to act
illegally, they also gain more control over what applications are running on
their networks.
AUDIT SYSTEM
Part of being a corporate member of FAST is to run a software audit,
discovering what applications are being used on the systems. This not only
identifies potential illegalities, but also allows the company's MIS
department to identify problem applications, usually unapproved packages
which have the potential to clash with either other applications or, more
significantly, the network management system itself.
This is certainly seen as a benefit by one of the recent additions to FAST
corporate members, Morgan Grenfell. The company also faced the problem that,
as its traders could not afford to be off-line while audits of their
individual systems were undertaken, it has had to utilise an on-line audit
system running on the network.
M-G sees some big benefits in this approach. Not only are the traders
minimally disrupted, for the audit is run over the network rather than their
individual computers being taken off-line, but once completed, the company
can then institute a continuous review process running automatically in the
background.
The company's Quality Management Group can also identify those applications
which, while perhaps not acquired through piracy (for example public domain
applications) are nonetheless not approved for use on the network. According
to the company's IT Quality Manager, Mike Marjot, this aspect of network
integrity and applications quality was the prime reason for the exercise.
Identifying illegally copied applications was, in a way, a very useful
by-product.
Given this perspective, the Quality Management Group decided they would tell
the traders and other users that the audit was taking place, and
specifically stressed that this was not being done to 'catch' anyone acting
illegally. Needless to say, that would have also been a very useful
by-product, particularly in advance of any unannounced visit from those nice
people from FAST.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Patents &amp; Licences.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-14131</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDTCVAGTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930420
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (16): The invisible 'glue' in IT
systems - . . . For OLTP Software
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST business transactions end up on a computer nowadays. A sales order
recorded from a telephone call, a withdrawal from an automatic teller
machine in the wall of a bank or a quote for an insurance policy - all
eventually find their way into a computer system somewhere.
Since computers were first used in commerce, there has been a demand for
these transactions to be executed in 'real time' or 'on-line' - giving rise
to the concept of on-line transaction processing (OLTP).
For many years this type of computing has been the exclusive province of
specially-built systems based on proprietary computer hardware. IBM's
mainframe computers are the best-known example - although all the leading
computer manufacturers offer comparable systems.
In the last few years, however, there has been a demand for a different kind
of OLTP. The spread of computer networks, which include equipment and
software from different suppliers, has forced OLTP into the wider market for
open systems. US market researchers at the Gartner Group expects this sector
is set to grow significantly in the next three years. It says that the total
market for mid-range transaction processing was worth Dollars 190m in 1992.
But by 1995, Gartner Group says it will be worth Dollars 3bn worldwide. It
goes on to say that this new market will be dominated by two OLTP software
products. Unix System Laboratories, Tuxedo and IBM's CICS/6000 are expected
to take over 50 per cent of the market between them.
CICS is, perhaps, IBM most successful software product with over 33,000
sites worldwide. It was originally developed for IBM's System/370 mainframes
over 25 years ago and has become the established market leader.
In September 1992, IBM announced a new, open version of CICS under the name
CICS/6000. This new version not only runs on IBM's RS/6000 Unix computers,
it is also being made available to other computer manufacturers - Hewlett
Packard being the first to take a licence.
Computer suppliers see OLTP as an important open systems' software
technology. Many companies rely on OLTP as the base for operational systems
such as accounting and customer-service support. Open systems must,
therefore, be able to cope with OLTP if they are to continue to grow and, in
the last two years, the standards infrastructure has grown to include the
mechanisms to make this possible.
The IBM-backed Open Software Foundation (OSF), for example, has published a
standard for distributed computing which covers this. It includes a
technique called the Remote Procedure Call (RPC) which can pass the complex
messages through a network, regardless of the operating environment or
computer hardware. IBM's new version of CICS uses the RPC to allow it to
work across different systems. Meanwhile Unix International, a rival faction
in the open systems market, has put its weight behind an alternative
transaction-processing system called Tuxedo. Although Tuxedo and IBM's CICS
look set to compete with each other in the market for open transaction
processing systems, they could end up co-operating. Tuxedo is able to work
with CICS systems already and IBM has announced that a version of Tuxedo
will be available for its mainframe computers - running with its AIX/Unix -
later this year. Unix International also supports many of the OSF standards
and there are strong pressures for the two standards to come together.
The International Standards Organisation (ISO) and the X/Open Group are also
working on a set of standards for open OLTP. These include the XA interface,
a standard which enables OLTP products from different manufacturers to
'talk' to each other. This means that a CICS system and a Tuxedo system can
co-exist on a network and exchange transactions.
The rush to provide OLTP software is not only restricted to traditional
suppliers like IBM, however. Database software suppliers, such as Oracle,
Informix and Sybase, have also identified OLTP as an important growth area.
They have added OLTP features to their database management software products
in the last few years - partly to expand their market, but also to meet a
growing demand for lower-cost OLTP systems.
NEW WAVE OF HARDWARE
Database software suppliers have also worked closely with a new wave of
computer hardware manufacturers to provide an alternative to the traditional
mainframe hardware platforms.
Companies like Sequent and Solbourne have built powerful computers by
plugging many small processors together. These systems rival the performance
of traditional mainframe systems and, when used with the new OLTP/database
software products described above, can support OLTP applications at much
lower cost.
OLTP is likely to become increasingly important in the context of office
systems and 'workgroup' computing, too. OLTP offers tried-and-tested
mechanisms which can ensure that important messages get from one part of a
network to another.
While this might not be especially important in simple electronic mail
systems, it becomes very important in the new breed of groupware
applications now beginning to surface. These applications need the type of
mechanisms offered by current OLTP software to ensure data integrity and
access security.
Groupware packages like Lotus Notes and FCMC's Staffware are being used to
automate work procedures such as loan approvals and sales calls. If they are
to be effective, they will need the same checks and controls used in
traditional OLTP applications.
OLTP software is the invisible 'glue' in modern information technology
systems and will become increasingly important as more and more business
transaction are conducted through computer networks.
</TEXT>
