<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (14): Workhorse of data
processing - . . . For Mainframes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT ONE time, a computer was a computer. Then Kenneth Olsen and his
colleagues at Digital Equipment invented the minicomputer, small,
comparatively inexpensive and environmentally friendly enough to sit in a
corner of the office, and a new name had to be found for the water-cooled
monster in the data centre.
Today, the mainframe computer is still the workhorse of commercial data
processing despite the advent of the personal computer and client-server
technologies which some believe will consign large machines to the dust-bin
of computer history.
Certainly the omens have not been good. The dwindling band of mainframe
manufacturers is in financial trouble because of a combination of
price-cutting - International Business Machines, for example, no longer
publishes mainframe list prices - and a trend among customers to networks of
personal computers and network servers which seem to offer better value for
money.
Mainframes are now made by only a handful of manufacturers. IBM, Unisys,
AT&amp;T through its NCR subsidiary, Control Data of the US, ICL of the UK,
Siemens Nixdorf of Germany, and NEC of Japan build machines of their own
design. Amdahl of the US, together with Fujitsu and Hitachi of Japan, are
'plug compatible manufacturers' (pcms) building mainframes that are
functionally identical to IBM's and able to run the same operating software.
While the financial problems mainframe makers face are real enough, the
notion that customers are turning away in droves from mainframes is an
illusion. There are many corporate data processing jobs which can only be
carried out efficiently by a machine with the power and flexibility of a
mainframe.
The essential historical difference between a mainframe and smaller computer
systems is the way information travels around the system. Mainframe
computers have channels, high speed data paths controlled by microprocessors
which move information to and away from the central processing unit at high
speed.
Minicomputers, on the other hand, typically use a 'bus', a single
information channel. Different kinds of information are separated on the bus
by elaborate timing mechanisms.
Now with the development of powerful microcomputers, the dividing line is
becoming blurred.
Some manufacturers, NCR, for example, are committed to building their entire
product line from personal computer to mainframe from combinations of
microprocessors.
Today, there is great interest in 'downsizing,' in moving from seemingly
expensive mainframes to networks of personal computers and servers, larger
machines which manage databases or carry out intensive computation.
SUBSTANTIAL SAVINGS
Such client-server systems seem to offer substantial economies, and in many
cases real savings can be made. Many application were run on mainframes only
because there were no alternatives and these translate easily to smaller
machines.
The decision to downsize from a mainframe is complex, however.
First, because some computing tasks - managing an airline reservation system
involving 3000 terminals, for example, can only be handled by a mainframe
with high speed channels.
Second, because the cost of supporting a client-server systems can be
substantially greater than for a mainframe.
Xephon, a UK-based consultancy, has estimated the cost of mainframe
computing over five years for a defined system configuration as between
Pounds 5,282 and Pounds 5,973 per user.
For a proprietary midrange system the cost rises to between Pounds 7,306 and
Pounds 7,786, for Unix systems Pounds 7,180 to Pounds 7,740 and for
networked personal computers, Pounds 9,400 to Pounds 15,500.
You can argue about the assumptions Xephon made, but its conclusion seems
clear: 'Far from being obsolete, mainframes currently offer the most
cost-effective computing facilities for all but the smallest organisations -
and will continue to do so for the foreseeable future.'
It is unlikely, however, that the value of the market for mainframe
computers will grow in the future. The demand for raw computing power will
certainly grow - at 40 per cent or more a year in some cases - but that will
be satisfied at the same or lower cost by improved technology and falling
prices.
CHANGING ROLE
The role of the mainframe is also likely to change. IBM , for example, which
has seen its profitability hurt by declining mainframe sales, is arguing
that the mainframe is the natural server in a client-server network,
offering network management, security and data integrity.
A second change is the emergence of open operating systems on mainframes.
Customers, in the past, had little option but to stay with their mainframe
supplier because of their investment in applications software designed to
run on a particular operating system - IBM's MVS, for example, or ICL's VME.
Particular operating systems were noted for particular qualities. Groupe
Bull's GCOS system, for example, is recognised for the quality of its
communications.
IBM already offers a Unix-like operating system, AIX on its mainframes. This
year it announced an open version of MVS in a move to make it easier to
accept a mainframe in a client-server network.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
