<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (15): Marriage with complicated
problems - . . . For Networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS impossible to think of computers in modern business without also
thinking about networks. The marriage of computers and telecommunications is
at the very heart of information technology and networks are the
'circulatory' system which provides the mechanisms for moving data and
messages from one computer to another.
There is, however, a fundamental problem. Networks are becoming increasingly
complex and need advanced software to control and manage them.
The increased complexity is the result of broader scope of modern
networking. Many different types of computer are being connected to networks
to provide the power for new applications.
In addition, the trend towards comprehensive digital networks - integrated
services digital networks (ISDN), for example - means that modern networks
must be capable of handling lots of different types of data simultaneously.
The promise of innovative applications like video-conferencing, multimedia
communications and workgroup computing will only come to fruition on the
back of more complex communications networks. But this places greater
demands on networking technology and makes it more difficult to manage and
control.
A survey of European businesses published last November by the networking
specialist 3Com noted that companies had 'serious reservations about the
value for money offered by their existing network investment.'
At the same time, nearly half of those surveyed recognised that they would
have continue expanding their networks to support the growth of their
businesses.
They cited a number of reasons for expansion, including: video-conferencing
to save money on business travel; electronic mail to improve internal
communications; and electronic data interchange (EDI).
Management of network growth is seen as a big problem. About three-quarters
of the network managers that 3Com surveyed said they expected problems in
expanding networks - especially in finding compatible services across
Europe.
ADVANCED APPLICATIONS
The increased use of networks for more advanced applications also poses a
significant operational management problem. Increasingly networks include
many different technologies and operating environments - each with its own
priorities and ways of working.
Monitoring network configuration and performance in this environment is a
nightmare. It embraces issues such as security of access, integrity of
shared data resources, disaster recovery and maintenance of systems response
times.
Most leading computer manufacturers have evolved products to control
networks which include both their own products and those of other leading
vendors. IBM's Netview and Hewlett Packard's Open view are examples.
Broader industry standards for network management have also begun to emerge.
The Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is one of the most prevalent.
SNMP is closely linked to the Unix open systems movement and a networking
protocol called TCP/IP. The TCP/IP protocol provides a language for systems
to 'talk' to each other and SNMP sits on top of it. If a fault occurs or
someone attempts to access the network without authority, the SNMP
mechanisms inform the central network manager software.
The International Standards Organisation (ISO) has devised a similar
standard called Common Management Information Protocol (CMIP). This is not
as popular as SNMP - although it has some advantages where communications
between different networks are needed.
Other efforts aimed at providing a comprehensive approach to network
management include those from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) and Unix
International. But the most comprehensive approach to enterprise-wide
network management comes from the Network Management Forum (NMF), an
industry body formed in 1988 which, unusually, includes computer users in
addition to suppliers.
NMF was formed to promote standards for network management right across the
board from standard 'voice' telephone systems to high-speed digital data
networks. It notes that standards bodies like ISO and the Consultative
Committee for International Telephone and Telegraph (CCITT) are only
concerned with standards for specific types of network, whereas NMF is
looking at the whole problem. NMF has published an Open Network Manager
Architecture in an attempt to synthesize the requirements for managing
different networks into a single specification.
GAINING SUPPORT
These specifications are gaining support from the industry and many
suppliers incorporate them within their own network management products.
NMP has also published a 'roadmap' showing the path that the development of
network management standards should follow in the future. What is most
likely to emerge from these efforts is a hybrid approach which allows for
the various standards to co-operate. Only then will complex problems of
network management begin to be solved.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
