<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (13): Success of the decade -
Laser printers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDITH MASSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN THE research organisation Dataquest asked businesses what they look for
in laser printers, compatibility and price came out at the top of the wish
list - beating speed and print quality hands down.
Dataquest's findings paint an accurate picture of laser printer products in
the 1990s. Organisations expect laser printers to be reliable, robust and
capable of producing excellent print quality. But they are still looking for
improvements in value for money, standardisation and flexibility.
Yet the laser printer has been the success story of the decade. Market
research company Romtec says that non-impact printers (a category which
includes inkjets and lasers) will dominate the UK printer market by 1994,
growing from a 49 per cent market share in 1991 to 67 per cent in 1994.
But when laser printers were first introduced in the mid-1980s, they were
expensive and unreliable. Pioneered by market leader Hewlett Packard (HP),
lasers are now the printer of choice for organisations which need a more
flexible approach to printing than the average daisywheel and dot matrix
device can provide.
The reason for the laser's success lies in its ability to produce limitless
typefaces and fonts, as well as graphics and drawings. An impact printer
like a daisywheel is incapable of producing more than one typeface on a
single page, or of producing any figurative images at all.
The fact that most of us now use graphical applications of one kind or
another - including word processors and spreadsheets with multiple font
sizes and styles - means that we demand more from printers. There is nothing
worse than creating a beautiful graphical document on-screen, only to see it
reduced to a tedious text-only format when it is printed.
Printer manufacturers have worked hard to bring laser technology down to the
level of the desktop, so that users can have a personal laser printer
attached to their PC. But the most exciting developments in laser printing
in recent months have not come on the desktop, but on the network.
THORNY ISSUE
Network printing has always been a thorny issue for large organisations. The
management of printers has become more difficult as PC software applications
provide more flexibility, because there has never been any guarantee that a
particular printer will obey commands generated from a particular word
processor or spreadsheet.
The result for large organisations has often been chaos, with confused
network servers being brought to their knees as users attempt to print
documents in fonts not available on the device that they have chosen.
Network operating systems have added to the problem, hiding printer
management functions deep inside their software - making it difficult for
anyone but the network manager to set up printer queues from multiple users
to output devices.
Recognising the difficulties that large organisations have with network
printers, operating system vendors like Novell and Microsoft have recently
added much better printer management facilities to their software. Novell
Netware 4.0 allows users to print documents more easily to remote devices,
while the Microsoft Windows Printing System simplifies the set-up of laser
printers with application software.
Printer manufacturers have also done their bit. HP's LaserJet 4 printer and
Bi-Tronics interface, which allows bi-directional communication between
printer and host, simplify processes such as printer set-up, network
printing and fault diagnosis. Instead of simply not printing, a laser
printer can use the Bi-Tronics interface to send a message to the user,
telling them that there is no paper, or that there is a paper jam inside the
printer.
PC manufacturer Compaq is a relative newcomer to the printer market, but
deliberately designed its first Pagemarq laser printers for network
printing. Pagemarqs are built around fast reduced instruction set computing
(Risc) processors and include more memory than the average laser printer.
They can also cope with different printer control languages used by
different software packages, and switch a utomatically between different
modes.
VALUE FOR MONEY
An emerging issue in laser printing is value for money. Although the price
of laser printers has fallen steadily, the cost of running and maintaining
them does not begin and end with the purchase price. Like copiers, laser
printers need to have toner and ink cartridges replaced regularly.
Manufacturers have now begun to measure the value for money achieved by
their printers in terms of cost per page, working out average costs over a
year.
Kyocera Electronics is pioneering the idea of lower printing costs,
comparing the running costs of its new Ecosys FS-3500 network printer (0.6
pence per page) against the 1.4 pence per page average of an equivalent H-P
printer.
Kyocera is keen to sell its laser printers as 'eco-friendly' machines that
use up fewer resources, as well as cost less money to run. But it will be
cost that drives organisations to choose better value for money laser
printers in the future. Kyocera's own research found that 75 per cent of UK
organisations would only buy from an environmentally conscious supplier if
its costs were competitive. Nevertheless, there must clearly be a place in
the future for cheaper laser printing.
Companies are also looking for cheaper colour lasers, which are still too
expensive for the average user. And while the growing use of Windows and
Netware will simplify the network printing process, there are still great
strides to be made in the way that software talks to printers. The days of
the plug-and-go network printer are still some time away.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
