<PROFILE>_AN-DDTCVAGIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930420
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (5): Applications for electronic
filing cabinets - . . .  For Database
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY'S electronic database has exactly the same problems as the
old-fashioned filing cabinet with drawers: retrieving information is never
as easy as it should be. Electronic data items do not get lost, mislaid or
mis-filed as paper items do. The main concern in the initial design of an
electronic database is the way data will be retrieved and used.
It takes the vision of a seer to predict every situation, every possible
detail which might prove of interest in the future. Even the
auspiciously-named Oracle, one of the leading database products which runs
on many different computers, can only deliver information that somebody has,
at some point, defined, collected and keyed-in. Once there, the data is
re-useable and can be shared between applications, and centrally updated.
A decade ago, buying a database was a heavyweight, long-term decision, taken
by IT experts who examined the entrails for predictions of performance by
running benchmark tests. Performance mattered because the database is often
the repository of information used in high volume transaction processing
applications. The coding of the applications was vital (and still is) to
performance, as is the organisation of data.
Users of automatic telling machines know they are sometimes slow in
response: there is probably a queue for the database as the details of the
account are accessed and delivered, using the account number as the 'key' to
retrieval. Relational databases allow any item or combination of items, (eg
name, age) to be used as a key.
MARKET LEADERS
Heavyweight database products, at the top end of the market, still account
for large chunks of the IT budget. They include IBM's stalwart of
transaction processing: the long-lived IMS, and its relational heir, DB/2,
as well as mainframe versions of Oracle, Software AG's and Computer
Associates' Datacom, and Cincom's Supra, successor to the phenomenally
successful Total, which dominated the database market in the 1970s. By the
early 1980s, minicomputer users had already discovered flexibility of
inbuilt databases such as in Pick systems and IBM's System 38, now AS400.
Then came PCs, and the boom in database applications under 'standard' PC-DOS
and later Unix operating systems.
Determining market penetration is less easy than it used to be, because of
the variety of hardware hosts in use. A few databases now run on a broad
range of computers, but the deciding factor in the 1990s is less likely to
be the computer host, performance, or even the development tools and data
access facilities available (see Q for Query languages).
The real selling point is more likely to be a specific application, and the
decision maker may not be an IT expert at all. In fact, a departmental
manager is now likely to buy a database by default, as part of an
application. This accounts for the rise of the value-added reseller (VAR) as
an important part of the sales chain, in many cases taking over the role
once fulfilled by the consultant.
Database vendors use 'runtime' licences for such situations. The end-user of
the application receives an abbreviated version of the database, rather than
the entire set of development tools.
Users are still able to use query languages for ad-hoc reports, though in
many cases they hardly know which database underpins their system.
Relational databases, built for ready retrieval of data, made it easier to
produce applications that could be closely tailored.
Many database vendors, particularly in the competitive mid-range Unix
market, now produce heavy tomes listing the various ready-made applications
available, ranging from specialised pig-breeding packages to everyday
accounting or marketing systems.
Informix, Ingres, Oracle and Progress are among the database vendors who
have built up a strong third-party 'stable' of VARs. Their directories serve
users, VARs, and ultimately their own ends, because once users have acquired
their primary application, they usually look for others from the same
database stable.
MORE THAN 120 PRODUCTS
The Progress Applications Catalogue lists over 120 products, claiming
100,000 applications licences. Informix's Solutions Guide lists hundreds of
applications, in 30 categories, one of which, accounting, offers 50 options.
Oracle estimates 350 applications from 130 VARs, who may hold multiple
development licences because of the various hardware platforms: one medical
specialist sells as many as 200 runtime licences a year.
Unlike many vendors of mainframe products on annual licences, PC and Unix
database vendors rarely know all their users. Oracle is launching a campaign
to locate all users, authorised or not. Tony Lacy-Thompson, senior product
manager at Informix, admits it is sometimes a problem to know who all
Informix end-users are, partly because work with OEMs, distributors and VARs
has been so successful: there are around 400 Informix VARs in the UK and
2,000 worldwide - 'runtime licences probably account for about 70 per cent
of the total licences, around half a million worldwide,' he says.
Traditionally, the only way to do it has been to include a registration
card, but they only have 2,000 names that way - 'now we've started issuing a
serial number and key. We only give out the key once people have registered,
and that gives us the opportunity to find our a lot about our users.'
</TEXT>
