<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (3): A measure of how data is
transmitted - . . . For Bandwidth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE thing that all new applications of computer technology have in common is
a demand for 'bandwidth.' Image processing, multimedia computing, voice-mail
and groupware applications are all examples of tasks that need a way to pass
large amounts of information back and forth very quickly.
In strict technical terms, bandwidth defines 'the difference, expressed in
hertz, between the two limiting frequencies of a band.' In practical terms,
bandwidth provides a measure of how much data can be transmitted from one
place to another in a given time.
Taking the analogy of a road transport system, bandwidth can be thought of
as the number of lanes on a motorway. If there are more lanes, then the
greater the number of vehicles which can use the road.
There are two obvious ways to increase the usable bandwidth of a
communications network. Firstly, the size of the 'pipe' which carries the
traffic can be made larger and more efficient. Secondly, the 'size' of the
data can be reduced or compressed so that more data can be carried in the
same 'pipe.' There are efforts under way to increase usable bandwidth in
both these areas.
The transition from analog to digital networks is one way to make the
communications 'pipe' bigger and better - either by using asynchronous
transfer mode (ATM) technology (see 'A') or integrated services digital
networks (ISDN). In both cases, data is carried through the network entirely
in a standard digital form, thus removing the need to translate it. This
increases transmission speeds and makes networks more efficient.
VIABILITY
Digital networks have been around for some time in the form of expensive
leased lines. These have only been viable for large organisations with a
continuous demand for a connection. It is only now, with the advent of
dial-up ISDN services, that the large bandwidth offered by digital
communications has become generally available and cost-effective.
UK telecommunications carrier Mercury says that, if line usage is less than
3.2 hours a day, the cost of a dial-up ISDN service is less than the cost of
a permanent leased line.
One of the main advantages of ISDN is that the bandwidth can be varied
according to the nature of the transmission. There are several different
ISDN services now becoming available - each rated according to the number of
'lines' they provide. The basic service offers two lines. More advanced
services provide as many as 30.
But these lines are not physical lines - they are logical lines, controlled
by the software. This means that many different messages can be carried
simultaneously using a single physical wire or optical fibre. If, however,
there is a need to carry a large amount of data - say, a broadcast-quality
video signal - several lines can be allocated to the task. Returning to the
road analogy - it is like carrying a wide load down two lanes of a motorway.
The other approach to increasing the usable bandwidth of a communications
network is to 'compress' the data with special hardware and software. If the
data transmitted across a network is reduced in this way, the traffic load
is, of course, also reduced.
There are number of approaches emerging to provide data compression.
In February, Microsoft announced its strategy for data compression which
will be built in to future versions of the MS/DOS operating system. Called
the Microsoft Realtime Compression Interface (MRCI), this specification will
give software developers a general-purpose mechanism to compress data in PC
systems. Microsoft says that MRCI will reduce data storage requirements. It
will also improve data transfer speeds between computers and between a
computer and its storage devices.
At the same time, the US software develop er Software Publishing (SPC)
announced a data compression technology for image data. It uses a technique
called fractal transform to convert images from strings of pixel information
into mathematical formulae. Fractal graphics have been used to create
lifelike computer graphics for some time now. SPC claims that the storage
requirements for a full screen, 24-bit colour image can be reduced from
about a million bits to as little as 10,000 by using the technique.
The combination of faster, more efficient communications networks and clever
data-compression techniques will help to remove many of the current
bandwidth restrictions. This will provide the foundation for many new
applications of information technology - particularly those which fall under
the heading of multimedia computing.
By the end of the decade it is conceivable that a standard desktop computer
will be able to provide full colour broadcast-quality images, hi-fi sound,
high-speed international communications and instant access to a multitude of
on-line services and databases. Much of the technology to achieve this is
already in place and it is only the lack of bandwidth which is the limiting
factor. Soon, even this limitation will be overcome.
</TEXT>
<XX>
