<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (2): Not so complex, really - . .
. For ATM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   IT SOUNDS complicated
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
but the idea of asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) communications technology
is essentially simple. It provides a common transport mechanism for digital
communications traffic, regardless of whether it is between computers on a
local area network (LAN) or across a public telephone network.
This is a significant breakthrough. It makes it possible to move data
between computers without the need to translate it into analogue formats.
Although LAN technology uses a digital format, most traffic carried across
wide-area telecommunications networks is still in analogue form. This means
that a modem is needed at both ends of the network to translate data between
analogue and digital form at and vice versa. In the long term, ATM
technology will make this unnecessary.
In the short term, ATM promises to boost the performance of LANs and allow
companies to be more flexible in the way they set up their networks.
According to the US market research company, CIMI, the average corporate
personal computer user changes office locations every 14 months - with
so-called 'power' users changing every seven months. This means that
companies must be able to re-organise their LAN frequently to cope with
changes in network traffic patterns.
The US manufacturer, Network Equipment Technologies (NET) says that ATM
technology makes it much easier for companies to do this. By using ATM
technology, they can set up a 'virtual' LAN which can be re-organized
quickly to cope with the changes.
Like current LAN technology, ATM uses 'packets' to carry data. But it uses a
fixed-size packet known as a 'cell.' Each cell contains only 53 bytes of
data, including five bytes used for addressing and directing data through
the network. An important advantage of ATM technology is that the cells can
be handled by hardware, which significantly increases the speed of
transmission. This is crucial when carrying voice and video signals - both
of which are, of course, time sensitive.
FASTER SYSTEMS
Existing LAN technology operates at a transmission rate of 10-16 megabits a
second - although there are faster technologies in the pipeline. Proposals
for a 'fast' Ethernet, one of the two leading LAN technologies, promises to
bring transmission speeds up to 100 megabits a second using existing
cabling.
In addition, there are moves to introduce a new standard called Fibre
Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) which also offers 100 megabits a second.
But ATM technology promises much greater transmission speeds. It starts at
155 megabits a second and has the potential to handle much higher rates up
to 2.4 gigabits. This scalability of ATM technology is one of its main
virtues and gives companies much greater flexibility in their use of LANs.
In the long term, ATM technology will also help to solve the problems
associated with moving data from one LAN to another through the public
telephone network.
The international standard for ATM communications has been agreed by all of
the world's leading telecom suppliers under the auspices of the CCITT.
Although it will be two or three years before the standard is fully
installed, equipment which conforms to it is now beginning to emerge and
opens up opportunities to improve the speed and efficiency of communications
between computers.
Large telecom suppliers - including AT&amp;T and MCI in the USA and British
Telecom in the UK - have promised to move to ATM technology for their
long-haul wide-area networks by the middle of the decade. Once in place, all
types of data can be carried from source to destination without the need for
any conversion. ATM opens the door to exciting new applications of computer
networks - especially those which involve moving large amounts of data about
such as video and audio. In the UK, for example, there are plans to upgrade
the Janet network, which links universities and research institutes, to ATM
technology. Known as SuperJanet, the new network will use ATM technology to
link 200 sites across the UK.
A pilot application to link six UK sites with ATM began in March 1993. When
it is complete, SuperJanet will be able to carry the large amounts of data
needed for applications like digital video and multimedia. One potential use
of the network will be for 'remote' medical consultancy where a team of
specialists will be able to observe and advise on an operation from
locations across the UK.
At the same time, commercial products which use ATM are beginning to emerge.
Hughes LAN Systems, a leading supplier of ATM technology demonstrated an
ATM-based digital video system at an exhibition in Washington, US, in March.
The demonstration used Hughes ATM switches to carry full-motion,
near-broadcast quality video images to five Sun SPARC Unix workstations.
Hughes says that the system can be used for applications such as video
conferencing, distributed training briefings and remote medical
consultations.
These early examples of the use of ATM communications show the exciting
possibilities of the technology.
</TEXT>
<XX>
