<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (1): The future of computing
starts here - Comment / Philip Manchester charts the trend towards a stable
infrastructure for information technology and the exciting new business
applications which this will allow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN casual observers of the computer and communications industries cannot
have failed to have noticed that things are changing. The inexorable rise of
the MS/DOS personal computer, the growth of networked systems and the
continued advances in both computer and communications technologies has
wrought change on a grand scale in the last couple of years.
These changes promise to create a stable continuum for future information
technology (IT) systems - but they mean a radical shift in the underlying
infrastructure of information processing which is both technological and
cultural.
On the technology side, new approaches to building and designing systems
using low-cost, high-performance hardware and standard 'open' software have
turned conventional wisdom on its head. Bigger is no longer necessarily
better and traditional IT is no longer competitive.
On the cultural side, the struggle to keep the IT industry the fast-moving,
high-growth industry it has been for the last 30 years, has led to
unprecedented alliances between erstwhile market rivals.
More important, the demands of computer users for genuine cost-effective IT
systems has forced suppliers to adopt a different approach to the design of
systems. It has also forced them to co-operate like never before.
The bottom line is that the new technology infrastructure of computers and
communications opens the door to exciting new applications.
But it also means that the world becomes more complex. In place of the
relatively simple computers of yesterday, modern users are confronted with
an array of technology to help them do their job.
This year's A to Z of Computing looks at the technological innovation which
has made this possible. Advanced digital telecommunications creates greater
bandwidth to carry more, richer information - opening the door to multimedia
applications.
The wide acceptance of the client/server architectural approach to networked
systems design, coupled with software standards such as SQL for databases
and X/Windows for workstation computing, makes it possible to build systems
from multi-sourced components.
NEW approaches to the application of IT - such as groupware, just-in-time
manufacturing, computer-aided systems engineering and voice technology -
provide opportunities for companies to gain competitive edge from their IT
investment.
At the same time, the growth of complex networks of computers raises
questions such as security, fault tolerance and software piracy.
While advances in IT do much to create new opportunities, traditional
approaches still have a role to play - although they will, of course, have
to change to survive. The mainframe computer still has much to offer - as
indeed does a traditional software discipline like as transaction
management. Future IT systems will be required to 'interoperate' with each
other at all levels to satisfy the growing need for a stable continuum of
technology from a handheld computer through to a powerful mainframe.
This future is being written now and the FT's A to Z of Computing places the
implication in context for the general reader as well as the technologist.
</TEXT>
