<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Food retailers lift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There were signs that the clouds might be lifting over the food retailers as
two leading securities houses turned more positive, although the shares
remained largely unmoved in lethargic trading.
Since the new year, the sector has been worried by a combination of price
war fears, the erosion of margins and the arrival of US-style discounters.
Brokers have responded by advising investors to go underweight.
Yesterday, NatWest Securities turned positive, arguing that 'the sector is
capable of growing earnings by at least 14 per cent per annum for the next
two years'. The threat of the discounters was dismissed as 'overdone', while
the large financial commitments of the majors was likely to keep price
competition fears in check.
SG Warburg took the opportunity to respond to the recent weakness in the
shares and Friday's retail price data, underlining its positive short-term
stance on the sector.
Both houses recommend Argyll Group, whose shares faded after an initial
spurt to close a penny down at 338p. NatWest upgraded its profits estimate
for the stock by Pounds 10m to Pounds 553m for 1994-95. Asda was also on the
NatWest buy list, with Kleinwort Benson also said to be positive yesterday.
The shares gained 2 1/2 at 68 1/2p.
</TEXT>
