<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Intel declines sharply after
court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices retreated yesterday, bringing the main indices down from the
record highs achieved at the end of last week, writes Patrick Harverson in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 11.62 easier at 3,466.99, but off
the day's low. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 shed 1.49 to 447.45, while the
American SE composite lost 1.66 at 418.26. New York SE volume was 245m
shares and declines led rises by 1,166 to 754.
The Nasdaq composite finished 3.75 off at 663.03 after a steep fall in Intel
shares.
Prices opened weaker, which did not surprise analysts. The Dow had advanced
to a record close on Friday, but the gains were primarily a result of
trading related to the monthly expiration of options contracts. Analysts
noted that it is quite common for stocks to reverse direction on a Monday
morning after an options-expiration rally in the previous session.
Although first-quarter corporate earnings continued to pour in, affecting a
number of issues, the spotlight was focused yesterday on technology stocks
after a landmark court ruling by a federal judge on Friday.
The judge's decision to set aside the verdict reached last year in a
copyright dispute between Advanced Micro Devices and Intel means AMD can now
begin manufacturing a clone of Intel's top-selling 486 microprocessor chip
while the two companies await a new trial.
News of the judgment sparked heavy and at times frantic trading in both
issues. AMD jumped Dollars 3 3/4 to Dollars 27 7/8 in volume of 5.4m shares,
while Intel, traded on the Nasdaq electronic market, plunged Dollars 12 1/4
to Dollars 97 3/4 in volume of 17.7m shares. The 486 chip that AMD will
begin cloning accounted for a substantial portion of Intel's Dollars 2bn of
first-quarter revenues.
A number of other technology issues declined in sympathy with Intel. Texas
Instruments lost Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 45 and Hewlett-Packard Dollars 1
1/4 to Dollars 73 1/4 .
Chrysler dipped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 42 in volume of 3.4m shares in
spite of news of first-quarter profits that exceeded market expectations.
Analysts put the decline down to profit-taking.
Leading airline issues weakened after Northwest Airlines fired the latest
salvo in the fierce domestic price-cutting war when it dropped fares on some
domestic and selected trans-Atlantic routes by as much as 35 per cent. UAL
fell Dollars 3 7/8 to Dollars 141 7/8 , AMR Dollars 2 to Dollars 66 5/8 and
Delta Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 56 3/4 .
Chase Manhattan shed Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 34 1/2 after the banking group
said it planned to raise Dollars 750m through a stock offering.
Canada
TORONTO gained further ground in another record volume as the smaller oil
and gas issues, along with diamond miners, continued to attract wide
interest and were traded in heavy turnover.
The TSE 300 index ended 11.4 higher at 3,663.2 and rises outpaced falls by
384 to 316 after volume of 90.7m shares valued at CDollars 601m. Monday's
volume included two large blocks in American Eagle Petroleum totalling about
12m shares.
Abitibi-Price, up CDollars  3/8 at CDollars 14 5/8 , reported reduced losses
from continuing operations in the first quarter and said it is considering
selling additional non-core assets.
</TEXT>
