<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Money Markets: France cuts two rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH FRANC futures rose modestly yesterday after the Bank of France cut
its intervention rate for the first time in five months, writes James Blitz.
The French authorities lowered their intervention rate, which sets the floor
for money market rates, from 9.10 per cent to 8.75 per cent. This was the
first time that the intervention rate had been cut since November 12 last
year.
The French authorities also reduced the 5 to 10-day lending rate, which sets
the ceiling for money market rates, from 10 per cent to 9.75 per cent.
The move, announced before European markets opened yesterday morning,
triggered an immediate rise in French franc futures prices. The June
contract, which closed at 91.76 on Friday night, opened at 91.87, peaked at
91.94 and ended at 91.89.
The cost of borrowing funds in the French franc cash market also fell back.
Three-month French cash closed at around 8.63 per cent, having finished at
some 9 per cent last Friday.
Dealers are clearly bullish about the prospect of more reductions in French
rates before the summer, believing it will soon be followed by more easing.
The June Pibor contract was last night pricing three-month money at 8.03 per
cent, some 60 basis points below the level of three-month cash.
The French franc's strong performance in the wake of the cut has also
further reduced the premium required by dealers for holding French francs
over D-Marks. The differential between three-month German and French cash
yesterday was down to 73 basis points. At the height of the crisis in the
exchange rate mechanism it was as high as 400 basis points.
Some dealers were also assuming yesterday that the cut in French rates might
herald further easing in the Bundesbank's official rates. The June Euromark
contract rose some 3 basis points on the day to close at 92.74.
Nevertheless, reasons remain for being cautious about predicting further
rate declines in Europe.
Sterling markets were quiet after last week's reduced expectations of a base
rate reduction.
Three-month rates closed softer at 6 per cent from a previous 6 1/16 per
cent. The June short sterling contract finished a basis point down on the
day at 93.92.
</TEXT>
