<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / International Company News: Intel share price plunges as
fresh trial is ordered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL'S share price plunged yesterday in response to an announcement late on
Friday that a new trial had been ordered in its copyright licensing dispute
with rival semiconductor manufacturer Advanced Micro Devices.
The court set aside an earlier decision preventing AMD from competing with
Intel in the lucrative market for 486 high-performance microprocessors used
in personal computers. Yesterday, AMD said it would enter the 486
microprocessor market immediately.
Intel's stock closed down Dollars 12 1/4 at Dollars 97 3/4 yesterday in New
York in very heavy trading, with 17.7m shares changing hands.
In a decision announced on Friday, US district court judge William Ingram
ruled that Intel had failed to produce documents that were relevant to the
copyright dispute, preventing AMD from getting a fair trial in litigation
decided last June.
Pending the outcome of the new trial, there is no legal barrier preventing
AMD from shipping microprocessors that incorporate Intel microcode, the
software that controls the functions of a microprocessor, AMD said.
AMD will begin shipments of a 486, using Intel's microcode, this month, but
will continue development of its own microcode and introduce new versions of
the 486 later.
'The worldwide computer industry has been held hostage to an unfairly
maintained monopoly on 486 microprocessors,' said Mr WJ Sanders, chairman
and chief executive officer of AMD.
</TEXT>
