<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / International Company News: Chrysler returns to black on
strong new model sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHRYSLER, the US car manufacturer which is bouncing back from financial
difficulties, yesterday underscored the success of its new model
introductions by reporting first-quarter earnings of Dollars 530m, excluding
accounting changes.
The profits compared with a loss of Dollars 231m, excluding special factors,
in the same period of last year, and were struck on sales and revenues up 33
per cent to Dollars 10.9bn from Dollars 8.19bn.
While the US vehicle market has been recovering only gradually from
recession, Chrysler's sales and market share have been rocketing due to the
introduction of several boldly-styled new vehicles, including its LH series
of full-sized cars.
The company's share of the US new vehicle market rose 2.5 percentage points
in the quarter to 15.5 per cent, while its sales volume rose 24.2 per cent.
First-quarter earnings per share totalled Dollars 1.57 before accounting
changes, ahead of the Wall Street consensus forecast, yet the company's
shares dipped Dollars 1 3/4 to close at Dollars 42 on the New York stock
exchange.
Mr David Healy, an analyst at S. G. Warburg Securities, said the share price
reaction was a 'bit of a mystery' in view of the results and was probably
due to profit-taking by investors.
A contributory factor could have been confirmation by Chrysler that its
plants would be affected by a lot of model changes in the third quarter.
The company reported a net loss for the quarter of Dollars 4.15bn, or
Dollars 12.81 a share, after taking a one-time non-cash charge of Dollars
4.7bn for a change in its methods of accounting for retirees' health
benefits. However, it warned Wall Street of the size of this charge at the
start of April.
Chrysler Financial, the group's financial services arm, reported
first-quarter earnings of Dollars 37m before a one-time Dollars 29m charge
for the same accounting changes.
That compared to Dollars 60m of earnings in the first quarter of last year
before a Dollars 51m gain from changes in new accounting standards for
taxes.
Chrysler Financial said the figures had been hit by higher borrowing costs
and lower levels of non-automotive assets, partly offset by lower credit
loss provisions.
In the first quarter of last year, the Chrysler group reported a net loss of
Dollars 13m, or 7 cents a share, after a one-time gain of Dollars 218m for
new tax accounting methods, a gain of Dollars 88m from a sale of shares in
Mitsubishi Motors, and a Dollars 63m loss on investments.
</TEXT>
