<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Chase Manhattan in share offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHASE MANHATTAN, the big New York bank engaged in a wide-ranging
restructuring programme, yesterday turned in higher first-quarter earnings
and revealed plans to raise Dollars 750m (Pounds 500m) of new equity capital
while also writing off Dollars 1bn of commercial property loans in a
significant change in strategy in the property sector.
Net profits for the quarter were Dollars 153m, up from Dollars 141m a year
ago. The net income was struck after a Dollars 500m extraordinary gain
reflecting accounting changes related to income tax.
The first-quarter 1993 profit also reflected special provisions of Dollars
884m taken after the bank decided to segregate about Dollars 2bn of 'lower
quality domestic commercial real estate assets' and to sell these in the
next few months. In addition to the charge the bank also used Dollars 135m
of its loan loss reserves, thus marking down the total value of the Dollars
2bn property portfolio to Dollars 1bn.
Mr Art Ryan, president of Chase, said selling the Dollars 2bn of property
assets would reduce the bank's bad debt provisions by Dollars 750m for the
rest of 1993.
Chase also said it had informed the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)
it planned to raise Dollars 750m of additional equity capital by way of a
share offer that will be underwritten by a syndicate led by Goldman Sachs,
First Boston, Merrill Lynch, Salomon Brothers and SG Warburg Securities.
Mr Tom Labrecque, chairman of Chase, said the aim of the property loan
disposal plan and share offer proposal was 'to take advantage of better
liquidity in the real estate market in order to shrink the size of the
property loan portfolio' while raising capital to continue financing the
bank's strategy of focusing on worldwide corporate, information and clearing
services and domestic New York area retail banking and consumer products.
At the end of March Chase's US commercial property loan portfolio totalled
Dollars 4.6bn, down from Dollars 8.2bn a year ago.
Chase also made other bad debt provisions of Dollars 360m, compared with
Dollars 300m a year ago. The bank wrote off Dollars 220m of loans in the
quarter, compared with Dollars 294m a year ago. Its tier one ratio of
risk-weighted assets to capital was 7.1 per cent at the end of the first
quarter, from 5.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
