<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Berisford offers 239p a share for Clark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BERISFORD International's proposed bid for C&amp;J Clark would be worth 239p a
share, the board of the private shoe company told shareholders in a circular
posted yesterday.
This is higher than the rumoured 205p a share, but includes 26p of deferred
cash relating to the sale of surplus Clark's property.
At 239p a share the company is valued at Pounds 184m. Clark said an offer of
239p would give a 165.6 per cent premium to the 90p at which the shares were
last traded and represented 19.9 times the average of the last three years
earnings per share.
The board said the offer was 'fair and reasonable' and seven of the 11
directors recommended it to shareholders. Three opposed the bid and one said
shareholders should be allowed to decide for themselves.
However, some family members who are against the sale were yesterday
consulting lawyers over the form of the proposals and legal action could
follow.
Clark board said that if Berisford, a food and property group, wins more
than 50 per cent of the votes at a special meeting to be held on May 7, but
its bid fails to gain 90 per cent acceptances, Clark would sell its business
to Berisford for cash and then recommend the liquidation of the company.
Berisford would only launch its bid if the proposal is approved at the
meeting. It would then offer 213p a share in cash, Berisford shares or
convertible loan stock. Surplus properties would then be sold and the
proceeds distributed to Clark shareholders.
Berisford said if Clark shareholders all took shares they would have a
majority of Berisford shares. Berisford shares were suspended at 128p
yesterday and will remain frozen until after the meeting.
The seven directors who recommended the bid said that 'there are no other
available alternatives which would provide a solution to Clark's
long-standing problems' and that the Berisford proposal was 'in the best
interests of Clark's'.
A statement from the three dissenting directors, who are non-executives and
family members, said Clark's three-year plan showed that the company could
be turned round to produce good profits and that 'it is unnecessary and
undesirable to sell C&amp;J Clark to Berisford'.
</TEXT>
