FT  20 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The programme chosen by David Attenborough as one of his 12 favourites from
the past 16 years of 'Wildlife On One' is indeed a classic. The methods
invented or adapted by producer John Downer to get film of birds in flight
included building a miniature camera into a radio controlled model plane
which was then disguised as a stork. This trick and others worked
astoundingly well, as you can see in Wildlife 100 (7.00 BBC1). Assignment
reports on the illegal trade in Russia's national treasures, especially
religious icons (7.45 BBC2). This has been going on for years but has
intensified since the collapse of communism. If Sailortown maintains the
standard set by the previous seven comedy pilots in this series it will be
quite appalling. This one is set in a Belfast pub (8.30 ITV). On the other
hand, if the second of three programmes about modern technology in Without
Walls is as good as the first it will be very well worthwhile (9.00 C4). The
hugely improved 40 Minutes uses tapes of original phone calls to document a
hair-raising incident when a Belgian banker's family was taken hostage (9.50
BBC2).
