FT  20 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Minister defends Group 4 service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was no reason yet to believe Group 4 Court Services was not up to the
job of operating Britain's first private prisoner escort service, Mr Peter
Lloyd, prisons minister, told the Commons home affairs committee yesterday.
Seven prisoners escaped or were wrongly released during Group 4's first
fortnight of running the service in the east Midlands, Yorkshire and
Humberside.
Mr Lloyd conceded that the Group 4 operation had got off to a disappointing
start and provided a 'field day for cartoonists.' But he believed the
principles behind contracting-out escort services, releasing police and
prison officers for other tasks, were correct.
He would not think the government had taken the wrong course unless similar
numbers of escapes continued in the coming weeks.
The committee was also told that in addition to his Pounds 125,000 salary,
Mr Derek Lewis, the television executive recruited by the government as
director general of the Prison Service, will qualify for performance related
bonuses of up to 35 per cent of his salary. Mr Lloyd said the formula for
calculating the bonuses had not been finally decided.
