<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Hurd wins backing for Bosnia
blockade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE MPs showed signs last night of rallying around a government
policy on Bosnia of toughening sanctions against Serbia and rejecting for
now - but not ruling out - an escalation of military action.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, won support among Tories for his pledge
to ensure the tightest possible enforcement of sanctions agreed by the UN on
Saturday. 'We are looking to turn sanctions into a blockade,' he said.
But he again faced calls from Labour for 'punitive' air strikes against Serb
supply and communication lines if the peace plan of UN negotiators Mr Cyrus
Vance and Lord Owen was not accepted. Some Labour left-wingers urged a more
forceful intervention.
Among Tory MPs, however, widespread fears about Britain being dragged into
an escalating conflict surfaced during Mr Hurd's statement.
Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister, last night flatly rejected
calls from Lady Thatcher, his successor in 10 Downing Street, for western
military intervention. Sir Edward, speaking after Mr Hurd's statement, said
that the West had no hope of settling the war by military means. Instead it
should concentrate its efforts on improving the supply of humanitarian aid.
Earlier in the Commons Mr Michael Ancram, Conservative MP for Devizes, said
positive military action might produce short-term results but could
'threaten a wide and bloodier civil war'.
Mr Nicholas Budgen, Tory MP for Wolverhampton South West, asked: 'What is
the British national interest in Bosnia?' He said the government needed to
explain what differentiated 'the horrible war in Bosnia from the many
equally horrible wars which are occuring in other parts of the world'.
Mr Michael Colvin, Tory MP for Romsey and Waterside, said the Serbs had
enough weapons to last two years and backed strongly the imposition of a
blockade. 'The umbilical cord between Moscow and Belgrade must be cut,' he
added.
For Labour, Mr Jack Cunningham, the shadow foreign secretary, said the
government had admited existing sanctions against Serbia had not been
properly enforced. He said it was time the Serbs were given an ultimatum
backed by the threat of air strikes.
</TEXT>
