<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Union warning to Timex strikers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRIKERS at the Timex company's plant in Dundee have been warned by their
trade union that it may expel them if they break the law in the course of
the dispute.
In a letter sent to each of the 340 strikers Mr Gavin Laird, general
secretary of the Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union, said:
'Failure to obey the instructions of the union's executive council will
render you liable to expulsion from the union.'
Since the beginning of the Timex strike 12 weeks ago the union has been
determined not to be involved in any unlawful action which would threaten
its own funds. Nevertheless the AEEU is going to unprecedented lengths to
protect itself from the dangers of litigation.
Mr Laird told the Timex strikers loss of union membership would lead to
withdrawal of the Pounds 30-a-week strike pay and other facilities. He added
that they could also lose their right to complain about unfair dismissal by
the company before an industrial tribunal if the union expelled them.
Mr Laird says in the letter: 'The executive council is seriously concerned
at reports received over the last few days about the escalating situation.'
Nevertheless, hundreds of the strikers' supporters have visited the picket
line outside the plant and others have held cash collections for them.
In an earlier letter Mr Laird told the strikers that any picketing that took
place outside the Timex plant had to be undertaken 'only by those who were
formerly employed by Timex and the union's officials and limited to six
people.
Today the Scottish TUC is debating the Timex strike and a large contingent
from the strikers is expected to lobby the delegates in Glasgow. Tomorrow
the AEEU's national committee will discuss the strike at its annual
conference.
Next week both the company and the union will present their cases before the
Commons employment committee.
The dispute aroused controversy after the company dismissed all its
employees for refusing to co-operate in a new working practices agreement
involving lay-offs and replacing them with a substitute workforce.
Timex has been unwilling to accept the intervention of the independent
conciliation service Acas to resolve the dispute.
</TEXT>
