<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Private rail plan scrutinised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday acknowledged for the first time that it was
considering a plan by a private-sector consortium to finance a much-needed
Pounds 900m upgrade of the railway line between London Euston, the Midlands
and north-west England.
Mr Roger Freeman, public transport minister, said: 'It's a very exciting
idea, and we are discussing with our colleagues in the Treasury how it would
work.' The government had also been approached with similar plans for other
lines, Mr Freeman said.
The scheme under consideration, prompted by the government's recently avowed
enthusiasm for attracting private finance into public-sector infrastructure
projects, has been proposed by three of Britain's biggest engineering
companies: GEC Alsthom, Trafalgar House and Balfour Beatty.
It would involve the renewal of worn-out tracks, replacement of signalling
and overhead electricity supply systems, realignment of curved sections of
track to allow faster train speeds, and replacement of some bridges.
One option for financing the scheme would be for the consortium to be
granted a limited-life concession to operate the line, upgrade it at its own
expense, and be paid by the government according to the number of trains
using the tracks.
The Pounds 900m bill for the project would also cover the purchase of a
fleet of trains to be provided by GEC Alsthom. However, Mr Freeman yesterday
said this part of the scheme might be funded separately under a Pounds 150m
leasing facility awarded to BR in last year's Autumn Statement.
Alternatively, the Pounds 150m could be used to lease more Networker
commuter trains which could operate on Network SouthEast's Kent Coast and
Great Northern routes. Tenders would be invited for both options, Mr Freeman
said.
</TEXT>
