<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Council tax allows town hall staff cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST COUNCILS in England and Wales have coped well with the introduction of
the council tax to replace the poll tax, a report today by the Audit
Commission, the local authority watchdog, shows.
The commission found in a survey that the change had allowed councils to
reduce staff by a planned average of 24 per cent.
The commission found that many councils still faced 'significant' backlogs
from the community charge which would take time to clear.
It found fault with two areas of council-tax implementation:
About 21 per cent of authorities face the danger of being left with computer
capacity they do not need, having bought equipment for the changeover
without an option of returning it.
More than 10 per cent of authorities have failed to monitor progress with
the council tax.
</TEXT>
